      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The organized opposition to the gospel in Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** This opposition was initiated by unbelieving Jews who maliciously influenced the Gentiles against the Christian believers.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Hostility to the gospel is not passive disagreement but active, malicious spiritual warfare that seeks to poison minds against God's people.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The organized opposition to the gospel in Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> This opposition was initiated by unbelieving Jews who maliciously influenced the Gentiles against the Christian believers.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Hostility to the gospel is not passive disagreement but active, malicious spiritual warfare that seeks to poison minds against God's people.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, fulfilling Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a textbook example of the primary obstacle the gospel consistently overcomes: deliberate, organized opposition rooted in unbelief.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse is the pivot point in the narrative of Paul's ministry in Iconium (Acts 14:1-7) during his first missionary journey. It directly follows a report of great success (v. 1) and immediately causes the division and persecution plot that forces the apostles to flee (vv. 4-6). It is the engine of the conflict in this episode.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):** The genre is **Historical Narrative**. The primary hermeneutic is to read this as a description of what happened, not a prescription for how to act (except in the apostles' perseverance). The narrator, Luke, records the event to show a recurring pattern: gospel success inevitably provokes satanically-inspired backlash (2 Tim 3:12).\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event occurs in the **New Covenant** era, under the dispensation of **Grace (the Church Age)**. It showcases the new dynamic of the church's mission, where the gospel goes to \"the Jew first and also to the Greek\" (Rom 1:16), and where opposition often arises from within the Jewish community, spilling over to incite the Gentile world.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This specific tactic—unbelieving Jews stirring up Gentile authorities or mobs against the church—is a repeating pattern in Acts, establishing it as a primary strategy of the enemy.\n    *   Acts 13:50 [Pericope: Acts 13:44-52 · source: NA28]: In Pisidian Antioch, \"the Jews incited the devout women of high standing and the leading men of the city, stirred up persecution... and drove them out.\"\n    *   Acts 17:5 [Pericope: Acts 17:1-9 · source: NA28]: In Thessalonica, jealous Jews \"formed a mob, set the city in an uproar.\"\n    *   Acts 17:13 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]: The same Thessalonian Jews traveled to Berea specifically to agitate and stir up the crowds there.\n    *   This fulfills Jesus's own warnings that his followers would be hated and persecuted (John 15:18-20).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, fulfilling Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a textbook example of the primary obstacle the gospel consistently overcomes: deliberate, organized opposition rooted in unbelief.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse is the pivot point in the narrative of Paul's ministry in Iconium (Acts 14:1-7) during his first missionary journey. It directly follows a report of great success (v. 1) and immediately causes the division and persecution plot that forces the apostles to flee (vv. 4-6). It is the engine of the conflict in this episode.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):</strong> The genre is <strong>Historical Narrative</strong>. The primary hermeneutic is to read this as a description of what happened, not a prescription for how to act (except in the apostles' perseverance). The narrator, Luke, records the event to show a recurring pattern: gospel success inevitably provokes satanically-inspired backlash (2 Tim 3:12).</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> This event occurs in the <strong>New Covenant</strong> era, under the dispensation of <strong>Grace (the Church Age)</strong>. It showcases the new dynamic of the church's mission, where the gospel goes to \"the Jew first and also to the Greek\" (Rom 1:16), and where opposition often arises from within the Jewish community, spilling over to incite the Gentile world.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This specific tactic—unbelieving Jews stirring up Gentile authorities or mobs against the church—is a repeating pattern in Acts, establishing it as a primary strategy of the enemy.<ul>\n<li>Acts 13:50 [Pericope: Acts 13:44-52 · source: NA28]: In Pisidian Antioch, \"the Jews incited the devout women of high standing and the leading men of the city, stirred up persecution... and drove them out.\"</li>\n<li>Acts 17:5 [Pericope: Acts 17:1-9 · source: NA28]: In Thessalonica, jealous Jews \"formed a mob, set the city in an uproar.\"</li>\n<li>Acts 17:13 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]: The same Thessalonian Jews traveled to Berea specifically to agitate and stir up the crowds there.</li>\n<li>This fulfills Jesus's own warnings that his followers would be hated and persecuted (John 15:18-20).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event takes place c. AD 47-48, during the first missionary journey of Paul and Barnabas, according to conservative Christian chronology (Hoehner). This is the foundational period of Gentile mission.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a major trade route. Its status as a crossroads ensured that both news of the gospel and the opposition to it would spread.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and, by extension, to the broader church. He is documenting the historical, Spirit-guided advance of the gospel to assure believers of its truth and to prepare them for the reality of opposition.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke, the careful historian (Luke 1:1-4), is compiling eyewitness accounts to create an orderly narrative. His purpose is apologetic and catechetical: to show that the Christian movement is the true fulfillment of God's promises and that its progress is unstoppable, even in the face of relentless hostility.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The event takes place c. AD 47-48, during the first missionary journey of Paul and Barnabas, according to conservative Christian chronology (Hoehner). This is the foundational period of Gentile mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a major trade route. Its status as a crossroads ensured that both news of the gospel and the opposition to it would spread.</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and, by extension, to the broader church. He is documenting the historical, Spirit-guided advance of the gospel to assure believers of its truth and to prepare them for the reality of opposition.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke, the careful historian (Luke 1:1-4), is compiling eyewitness accounts to create an orderly narrative. His purpose is apologetic and catechetical: to show that the Christian movement is the true fulfillment of God's promises and that its progress is unstoppable, even in the face of relentless hostility.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\nThis single verse is a concise diagnosis of spiritual warfare, built on three powerful Greek verbs.\n\n*   **The Root of Opposition: ἀπειθήσαντες (*apeithēsantes*, \"having disobeyed / disbelieved\").** This is not intellectual doubt but willful rebellion. The aorist participle identifies the foundational act: they heard the gospel (v. 1) and refused to obey its claim. In biblical thought, belief is a form of obedience, and unbelief is disobedience (cf. John 3:36; Rom 10:16). Their subsequent actions flow from this root rejection.\n\n*   **The Method of Opposition, Part 1: ἐπήγειραν (*epēgeiran*, \"they stirred up / incited\").** This verb depicts active agitation. They did not simply disagree; they went out and instigated trouble. They became agents of unrest, deliberately provoking the Gentiles who may have otherwise been neutral or even curious. This reveals opposition as a work of recruitment.\n\n*   **The Method of Opposition, Part 2: ἐκάκωσαν (*ekakōsan*, \"they made evil / poisoned / embittered\").** This is the most chilling verb. From the root κακός (*kakos*, \"evil\"), it means to corrupt something's nature, to make it evil. They didn't just present counterarguments; they poisoned the very souls—τὰς ψυχὰς (*tas psychas*)—of the Gentiles. This is slander, misrepresentation, and the stoking of fear and hatred. The target is the inner disposition, turning hearts and minds hostile before the gospel can even be fairly heard. The battle is for the soul.\n\n*   **The Target of Opposition: κατὰ τῶν ἀδελφῶν (*kata tōn adelphōn*, \"against the brothers\").** The ultimate target is the people of God, identified by their familial relationship in Christ. The attack is personal and communal. It seeks to isolate and destroy the fellowship of believers.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<p>This single verse is a concise diagnosis of spiritual warfare, built on three powerful Greek verbs.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>The Root of Opposition: ἀπειθήσαντες (<em>apeithēsantes</em>, \"having disobeyed / disbelieved\").</strong> This is not intellectual doubt but willful rebellion. The aorist participle identifies the foundational act: they heard the gospel (v. 1) and refused to obey its claim. In biblical thought, belief is a form of obedience, and unbelief is disobedience (cf. John 3:36; Rom 10:16). Their subsequent actions flow from this root rejection.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>The Method of Opposition, Part 1: ἐπήγειραν (<em>epēgeiran</em>, \"they stirred up / incited\").</strong> This verb depicts active agitation. They did not simply disagree; they went out and instigated trouble. They became agents of unrest, deliberately provoking the Gentiles who may have otherwise been neutral or even curious. This reveals opposition as a work of recruitment.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>The Method of Opposition, Part 2: ἐκάκωσαν (<em>ekakōsan</em>, \"they made evil / poisoned / embittered\").</strong> This is the most chilling verb. From the root κακός (<em>kakos</em>, \"evil\"), it means to corrupt something's nature, to make it evil. They didn't just present counterarguments; they poisoned the very souls—τὰς ψυχὰς (<em>tas psychas</em>)—of the Gentiles. This is slander, misrepresentation, and the stoking of fear and hatred. The target is the inner disposition, turning hearts and minds hostile before the gospel can even be fairly heard. The battle is for the soul.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>The Target of Opposition: κατὰ τῶν ἀδελφῶν (<em>kata tōn adelphōn</em>, \"against the brothers\").</strong> The ultimate target is the people of God, identified by their familial relationship in Christ. The attack is personal and communal. It seeks to isolate and destroy the fellowship of believers.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This verse is a clear expression of the enmity between the seed of the serpent and the seed of the woman promised in Genesis 3:15. This spiritual conflict runs through the entire Bible.\n    *   **Hinge Texts:** Cain's murder of Abel (1 John 3:12), the persecution of the prophets (Matt 23:34-35), the crucifixion of Christ by the hands of lawless men stirred up by their leaders (Acts 2:23), and the ongoing war against the saints (Rev 12:17).\n    *   **Hinge-of-Hinges:** The Cross, where the ultimate act of hostility was turned by God into the ultimate victory over the powers of darkness (Col 2:15).\n    *   **Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\"):** This trajectory terminates in the final judgment of the \"accuser of our brothers\" (Rev 12:10) and the vindication of the saints at Christ's return. The terminus verse is Revelation 20:10.\n\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag**\n    *   **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"):** This verse shows sin not as a passive state but as an active, malevolent force that despises God's grace and actively works to suppress it.\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** It establishes that persecution and slander are normative experiences for the church on mission in a fallen world. The church is a fellowship of \"brothers\" forged in the midst of hostility.\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** It highlights the spiritual battle that surrounds the proclamation of the gospel. Salvation is an act of rescue from a world system actively hostile to God.\n    *   **Angelology (\"the doctrine of angels, demons, and the spiritual realm\"):** While the agents are human, the strategy of slander and mind-poisoning is characteristic of Satan, \"the father of lies\" (John 8:44) and the \"accuser of the brothers\" (Rev 12:10).\n\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ by confirming His predictions of persecution (John 15:20, \"If they persecuted me, they will also persecute you\") and by demonstrating the very darkness that He came to overcome. The apostles' perseverance in the face of this hostility is a direct reflection of Christ's own steadfastness on His way to the cross.\n",
