      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The public response to the gospel proclamation in the city of Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** The gospel message inherently forces a division, compelling the populace to align either with its opponents or with its messengers.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** The proclamation of Christ is not neutral; it is a divisive power that splits communities by demanding ultimate allegiance.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The public response to the gospel proclamation in the city of Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> The gospel message inherently forces a division, compelling the populace to align either with its opponents or with its messengers.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> The proclamation of Christ is not neutral; it is a divisive power that splits communities by demanding ultimate allegiance.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This verse exemplifies a recurring pattern in that expansion: faithful proclamation of the gospel (14:3) inevitably leads to societal division and opposition (14:2, 4), which in turn propels the mission forward (14:6).\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse sits in the account of Paul's first missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It forms the pivot point in the Iconium narrative (14:1-7), explaining the tension that forces Paul and Barnabas to flee to Lystra and Derbe. The sequence is: proclamation (v. 1) → opposition (v. 2) → perseverance & confirmation (v. 3) → **division (v. 4)** → conspiracy & flight (vv. 5-7).\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):** The genre is Historical Narrative. The primary hermeneutic is to distinguish description from prescription: Luke records what happened, which reveals a pattern of gospel advance, but does not command believers to seek division. The narrative demonstrates that division is a necessary, though often painful, consequence of faithfulness to the message.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event occurs in the early Church Age, under the dispensation of Grace. The New Covenant is being proclaimed to both Jews and Gentiles, demonstrating that the wall of hostility has been broken down *in Christ* (Eph 2:14), even as the message itself creates new lines of division in the world.\n*   **Author & Attribution:** Luke the physician, companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), is the author by unanimous early church tradition. The \"we\" passages in Acts (16:10-17; 20:5-15; 21:1-18; 27:1–28:16) confirm the author was an eyewitness to parts of the story. The book was likely written in the early AD 60s.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The preceding verse (14:3) shows the Lord bearing witness to the \"word of His grace\" with signs and wonders. The subsequent verse (14:5) shows the division escalating into a violent plot. This verse (14:4) is the crucial link, showing that even divinely-attested grace does not produce universal acceptance but sharpens the division.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This pattern of gospel-induced division is a theme in Acts (Acts 13:45-50 in Antioch; 17:4-5 in Thessalonica; 18:6 in Corinth; 28:24 in Rome). It fulfills Jesus' own prophetic words that His coming would bring division, not peace (Luke 12:51-53; Matt 10:34-36).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This verse exemplifies a recurring pattern in that expansion: faithful proclamation of the gospel (14:3) inevitably leads to societal division and opposition (14:2, 4), which in turn propels the mission forward (14:6).</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse sits in the account of Paul's first missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It forms the pivot point in the Iconium narrative (14:1-7), explaining the tension that forces Paul and Barnabas to flee to Lystra and Derbe. The sequence is: proclamation (v. 1) → opposition (v. 2) → perseverance &amp; confirmation (v. 3) → <strong>division (v. 4)</strong> → conspiracy &amp; flight (vv. 5-7).</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):</strong> The genre is Historical Narrative. The primary hermeneutic is to distinguish description from prescription: Luke records what happened, which reveals a pattern of gospel advance, but does not command believers to seek division. The narrative demonstrates that division is a necessary, though often painful, consequence of faithfulness to the message.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> This event occurs in the early Church Age, under the dispensation of Grace. The New Covenant is being proclaimed to both Jews and Gentiles, demonstrating that the wall of hostility has been broken down <em>in Christ</em> (Eph 2:14), even as the message itself creates new lines of division in the world.</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> Luke the physician, companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), is the author by unanimous early church tradition. The \"we\" passages in Acts (16:10-17; 20:5-15; 21:1-18; 27:1–28:16) confirm the author was an eyewitness to parts of the story. The book was likely written in the early AD 60s.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The preceding verse (14:3) shows the Lord bearing witness to the \"word of His grace\" with signs and wonders. The subsequent verse (14:5) shows the division escalating into a violent plot. This verse (14:4) is the crucial link, showing that even divinely-attested grace does not produce universal acceptance but sharpens the division.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This pattern of gospel-induced division is a theme in Acts (Acts 13:45-50 in Antioch; 17:4-5 in Thessalonica; 18:6 in Corinth; 28:24 in Rome). It fulfills Jesus' own prophetic words that His coming would bring division, not peace (Luke 12:51-53; Matt 10:34-36).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event takes place during Paul's first missionary journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m / 3370 ft) was a major city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a high, arid plateau. It was a strategic stop on the major trade route (the *Via Sebaste*) connecting Ephesus to Syria, making it a cosmopolitan center.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The city's population, τὸ πλῆθος (*to plēthos*, \"the multitude\"), was a mix of native Phrygians, Greek settlers, a Roman administrative class, and a significant Jewish community with its own synagogue (Acts 14:1).\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is writing to Theophilus (Acts 1:1), likely a high-ranking Roman official, to provide an \"orderly account\" of the origins of the Christian faith. This verse serves to explain to a Roman mind, accustomed to valuing social order (*pax Romana*), why the Christian message often resulted in civic unrest. It wasn't the apostles' intent, but the message's very nature.\n*   **Socio-Political Background:** As a Roman city, Iconium valued public peace. Any movement that caused a σχίσμα (*schisma*, \"division\") would attract the attention of city magistrates. The opposition's strategy was often to frame the apostles as disturbers of the peace (cf. Acts 17:6, \"These men who have turned the world upside down have come here also\").\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The event takes place during Paul's first missionary journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m / 3370 ft) was a major city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a high, arid plateau. It was a strategic stop on the major trade route (the <em>Via Sebaste</em>) connecting Ephesus to Syria, making it a cosmopolitan center.</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> The city's population, τὸ πλῆθος (<em>to plēthos</em>, \"the multitude\"), was a mix of native Phrygians, Greek settlers, a Roman administrative class, and a significant Jewish community with its own synagogue (Acts 14:1).</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke is writing to Theophilus (Acts 1:1), likely a high-ranking Roman official, to provide an \"orderly account\" of the origins of the Christian faith. This verse serves to explain to a Roman mind, accustomed to valuing social order (<em>pax Romana</em>), why the Christian message often resulted in civic unrest. It wasn't the apostles' intent, but the message's very nature.</li>\n<li><strong>Socio-Political Background:</strong> As a Roman city, Iconium valued public peace. Any movement that caused a σχίσμα (<em>schisma</em>, \"division\") would attract the attention of city magistrates. The opposition's strategy was often to frame the apostles as disturbers of the peace (cf. Acts 17:6, \"These men who have turned the world upside down have come here also\").</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The verse states a simple historical fact: the city's population split into two camps. One sided with the established Jewish community leadership that was opposing the gospel, and the other sided with the messengers of that gospel.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The key verb is ἐσχίσθη (*eschisthē*), the aorist passive indicative of σχίζω (*schizō*), meaning \"to tear, rend, split.\"\n    *   **The Passive Voice:** This is likely a \"divine passive,\" subtly indicating that God is the ultimate agent behind this division. The gospel, by God's design, acts as a clarifying agent that forces a choice.\n    *   **The Aorist Tense:** This points to a specific, decisive event. The division wasn't a slow drift but a definite cleaving of the community that happened as a result of the events in verses 1-3.\n    *   **The Lexical Choice:** σχίζω (*schizō*) is a strong, almost violent word. It's used for the tearing of a garment (Matt 27:51, the temple veil) or a fishing net (John 21:11). It implies a painful, decisive rupture in the social fabric, not a polite disagreement. This is the root of the English word \"schism.\"\n*   **Wordplay:** The use of the μὲν...δὲ (*men...de*) construction creates a perfectly balanced antithesis: \"on the one hand... on the other hand.\" This grammatical structure mirrors the social reality: two distinct, opposing camps were formed. There was no middle ground.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The image is one of a city being torn in two. This powerfully illustrates the non-negotiable claims of Jesus Christ. The gospel is a \"sword\" (Matt 10:34) that cuts through all other allegiances—family, ethnicity, civic identity—and re-forms a new community around allegiance to Him alone.\n*   **Common Misreadings Flag:**\n    *   *Misreading:* Christians should seek to create division and conflict to prove their faithfulness.\n    *   *Why wrong:* The apostles preached a message of grace and peace (Acts 10:36; Eph 2:17). The division was the *result* of the world's hostile reaction to that message, not the *goal* of the apostles' ministry.\n    *   *Cross-references:* Romans 12:18; Hebrews 12:14.\n    *   *Correct reading:* Believers must anticipate that faithfulness to the gospel will be divisive in a fallen world and should not be surprised or deterred by opposition.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter:</strong> The verse states a simple historical fact: the city's population split into two camps. One sided with the established Jewish community leadership that was opposing the gospel, and the other sided with the messengers of that gospel.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The key verb is ἐσχίσθη (<em>eschisthē</em>), the aorist passive indicative of σχίζω (<em>schizō</em>), meaning \"to tear, rend, split.\"<ul>\n<li><strong>The Passive Voice:</strong> This is likely a \"divine passive,\" subtly indicating that God is the ultimate agent behind this division. The gospel, by God's design, acts as a clarifying agent that forces a choice.</li>\n<li><strong>The Aorist Tense:</strong> This points to a specific, decisive event. The division wasn't a slow drift but a definite cleaving of the community that happened as a result of the events in verses 1-3.</li>\n<li><strong>The Lexical Choice:</strong> σχίζω (<em>schizō</em>) is a strong, almost violent word. It's used for the tearing of a garment (Matt 27:51, the temple veil) or a fishing net (John 21:11). It implies a painful, decisive rupture in the social fabric, not a polite disagreement. This is the root of the English word \"schism.\"</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Wordplay:</strong> The use of the μὲν...δὲ (<em>men...de</em>) construction creates a perfectly balanced antithesis: \"on the one hand... on the other hand.\" This grammatical structure mirrors the social reality: two distinct, opposing camps were formed. There was no middle ground.</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):</strong> The image is one of a city being torn in two. This powerfully illustrates the non-negotiable claims of Jesus Christ. The gospel is a \"sword\" (Matt 10:34) that cuts through all other allegiances—family, ethnicity, civic identity—and re-forms a new community around allegiance to Him alone.</li>\n<li><strong>Common Misreadings Flag:</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Misreading:</em> Christians should seek to create division and conflict to prove their faithfulness.</li>\n<li><em>Why wrong:</em> The apostles preached a message of grace and peace (Acts 10:36; Eph 2:17). The division was the <em>result</em> of the world's hostile reaction to that message, not the <em>goal</em> of the apostles' ministry.</li>\n<li><em>Cross-references:</em> Romans 12:18; Hebrews 12:14.</li>\n<li><em>Correct reading:</em> Believers must anticipate that faithfulness to the gospel will be divisive in a fallen world and should not be surprised or deterred by opposition.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This event is a fulfillment of Christ's own prophecy. Jesus declared, \"Do you think that I have come to give peace on earth? No, I tell you, but rather division\" (Luke 12:51) [PROPHECY]. The division at Iconium is a localized manifestation of this universal principle.\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif is the \"Two Ways\" or the \"Great Divide.\"\n    *   It begins in the Torah with the choice between life and death, blessing and curse (Deut 30:19).\n    *   It continues in the Wisdom literature with the path of the righteous versus the path of the wicked (Psalm 1).\n    *   It is personified in Jesus, who is the narrow gate that few find (Matt 7:13-14) and the stone that causes some to stumble and others to rise (Luke 2:34).\n    *   The *hinge-of-hinges* is the Cross, which is either the wisdom and power of God or foolishness and a stumbling block (1 Cor 1:18-25).\n    *   The *terminus verse* is 2 Corinthians 2:15-16, where Paul describes the apostles as the \"aroma of Christ,\" an aroma of death to those who are perishing, and an aroma of life to those who are being saved. Acts 14:4 is the narrative demonstration of this truth.\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** The gospel is not merely an offer but a power that actively sorts humanity. Its reception or rejection has immediate social consequences.\n    *   ☐ **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** The church is formed by being called *out of* the world. This verse shows the birth pangs of a local church as it is distinguished from the opposing community.\n    *   ☐ **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"):** Sinful humanity's natural reaction to the light of the gospel is often hostility and rejection (John 3:19-20).\n    *   ☐ **Missiology (sub-locus of Ecclesiology):** This verse establishes a realistic theology of missions. Missionaries should expect opposition and division as a normal part of their work.\n*   **Theological Tension / Paradox:** The gospel is simultaneously a message of ultimate reconciliation (2 Cor 5:18-20; Eph 2:14-16) and the cause of immediate division (Luke 12:51). The tension is resolved in this: it reconciles man to God and creates a new, unified humanity (the Church), but in doing so, it necessarily divides that new humanity from the world that remains in rebellion.\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ as the great dividing line of human history. One's relationship to Him, as proclaimed by His apostles, determines one's ultimate allegiance and destiny. He is the rock on which people are either established or broken (Matt 21:44).\n",
