t rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single ` ```text ` fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and are within the 5-9 syllable limit.\nGate 24: PASS — Title is 4 words, concrete, from Chorus, and memorable.\n\n```text\nTitle: A Plot in the Dust\nStyle: Folk rock, male vocalist, sparse arrangement, driving acoustic guitar, floor tom, upright bass, subtle mandolin, recorded in a wooden room, analog tape warmth, no digital effects\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nA word of life was sown (A)\nOn hearts as hard as stone (A)\nThe city split in two (B)\nThe old against the new (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe rulers give the nod (A)\nAgainst the men of God (A)\nA plot is in the dust (B)\nFueled by hateful trust (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nThey whisper in the street (A)\nA plan of harsh deceit (A)\nFirst shame them with disgrace (B)\nThen crush them in this place (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe rulers give the nod (A)\nAgainst the men of God (A)\nA plot is in the dust (B)\nFueled by hateful trust (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nO Lord, they hate Your light (A)\nAnd gather in the night (A)\nWe walk the path You trod (B)\nThe servant, like his God (B)\n\n[Outro]\nTheir hands reach for a rock (A)\nWe hear the turning lock (A)\nBut You provide the way (B)\nTo preach another day (B)\n```\n\n### Legend & Key\n*   **Metaphor:** The central image is the \"plot in the dust\"—a conspiracy born from the earth-bound, fallen nature of man against the heaven-sent gospel.\n*   **Chorus:** Directly summarizes Acts 14:5—the coalition of rulers, Gentiles (\"hateful trust\"), and Jews (\"plot in the dust\") against the apostles (\"men of God\").\n*   **Verse 1:** Sets the context from Acts 14:1-4, where the preaching of the \"word of life\" leads to belief (\"sown\") but also division (\"the city split in two\").\n*   **Verse 2:** Expands on the two-fold intent of the plot: public shaming (ὑβρίσαι, *hybrisai*, \"shame them with disgrace\") and stoning (λιθοβολῆσαι, *lithobolēsai*, \"crush them in this place\").\n*   **Bridge:** Provides the Christo-telic connection. The opposition is ultimately against God (\"they hate Your light\"). The apostles' suffering is a participation in Christ's own rejection (\"We walk the path You trod / The servant, like his God,\" referencing John 15:20). It includes the vocative address (\"O Lord\") and first-person enrolment (\"We walk\").\n*   **Outro:** Narrates the escape from Acts 14:6. The threat is imminent (\"hands reach for a rock\"), but God provides deliverance (\"You provide the way\") for the sake of the ongoing mission (\"To preach another day\").\n",
