      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The unified opposition of Gentiles, Jews, and their rulers against Paul and Barnabas in Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** This opposition escalated from civic division into a specific, violent plot to publicly humiliate and execute the apostles by stoning.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Faithful gospel ministry inevitably provokes a unified and violent hostility from the world's religious and secular powers, requiring Spirit-led wisdom to preserve the mission.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The unified opposition of Gentiles, Jews, and their rulers against Paul and Barnabas in Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> This opposition escalated from civic division into a specific, violent plot to publicly humiliate and execute the apostles by stoning.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Faithful gospel ministry inevitably provokes a unified and violent hostility from the world's religious and secular powers, requiring Spirit-led wisdom to preserve the mission.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered advance of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth against persistent opposition (Acts 1:8). This verse is a textbook example of that theme, showing how persecution, rather than stopping the mission, often redirects it into new fields of ministry.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse is the crisis point in the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28), specifically within the Iconium episode (Acts 14:1-7). The plot described here is the direct cause for the apostles' flight to Lystra and Derbe, propelling the journey forward.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):** The genre is **Historical Narrative** with a strong **Persecution/Suffering Overlay**.\n    *   *Narrative Rule:* We read this descriptively, not prescriptively. It records the reality of opposition, not a model for creating it.\n    *   *Persecution Rule:* The suffering here is the threat of mob violence and execution by stoning. The apostles' response models the principle of fleeing persecution when possible to preserve the mission (Matt 10:23), demonstrating that such flight is not cowardice but wise stewardship. This suffering conforms them to the pattern of Christ, who faced similar plots (John 8:59).\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The events occur within the **New Covenant** era, during the **Age of Grace** (the Church Age). The gospel is being taken to the Gentiles in fulfillment of Old Testament promises, and the apostles are operating under the authority of the Great Commission.\n*   **Author & Attribution:** Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing around AD 60-62. This is the second volume of his two-part work, Luke-Acts.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The preceding verses (14:1-4) describe the initial success of the gospel in Iconium, which leads to a sharp division within the city. This verse (14:5) is the violent result of that division. The following verses (14:6-7) narrate the apostles' prudent escape and the continuation of their ministry elsewhere.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This event is part of a recurring pattern in Acts where gospel proclamation leads to persecution (Acts 13:50 [Pericope: Acts 13:42-52 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:5-10 [Pericope: Acts 17:1-15 · source: NA28]). It fulfills Jesus' own warnings (Matt 10:16-23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-25 · source: NA28]; John 15:20 [Pericope: John 15:18-27 · source: NA28]) and is later recalled in Paul's \"suffering lists\" (2 Cor 11:23-28 [Pericope: 2 Cor 11:16-33 · source: NA28]). The coalition of \"Gentiles and Jews with their rulers\" echoes the conspiracy against Jesus Himself (Acts 4:27 [Pericope: Acts 4:23-31 · source: NA28], quoting Ps 2:1-2).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered advance of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth against persistent opposition (Acts 1:8). This verse is a textbook example of that theme, showing how persecution, rather than stopping the mission, often redirects it into new fields of ministry.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse is the crisis point in the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28), specifically within the Iconium episode (Acts 14:1-7). The plot described here is the direct cause for the apostles' flight to Lystra and Derbe, propelling the journey forward.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):</strong> The genre is <strong>Historical Narrative</strong> with a strong <strong>Persecution/Suffering Overlay</strong>.<ul>\n<li><em>Narrative Rule:</em> We read this descriptively, not prescriptively. It records the reality of opposition, not a model for creating it.</li>\n<li><em>Persecution Rule:</em> The suffering here is the threat of mob violence and execution by stoning. The apostles' response models the principle of fleeing persecution when possible to preserve the mission (Matt 10:23), demonstrating that such flight is not cowardice but wise stewardship. This suffering conforms them to the pattern of Christ, who faced similar plots (John 8:59).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> The events occur within the <strong>New Covenant</strong> era, during the <strong>Age of Grace</strong> (the Church Age). The gospel is being taken to the Gentiles in fulfillment of Old Testament promises, and the apostles are operating under the authority of the Great Commission.</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing around AD 60-62. This is the second volume of his two-part work, Luke-Acts.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The preceding verses (14:1-4) describe the initial success of the gospel in Iconium, which leads to a sharp division within the city. This verse (14:5) is the violent result of that division. The following verses (14:6-7) narrate the apostles' prudent escape and the continuation of their ministry elsewhere.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This event is part of a recurring pattern in Acts where gospel proclamation leads to persecution (Acts 13:50 [Pericope: Acts 13:42-52 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:5-10 [Pericope: Acts 17:1-15 · source: NA28]). It fulfills Jesus' own warnings (Matt 10:16-23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-25 · source: NA28]; John 15:20 [Pericope: John 15:18-27 · source: NA28]) and is later recalled in Paul's \"suffering lists\" (2 Cor 11:23-28 [Pericope: 2 Cor 11:16-33 · source: NA28]). The coalition of \"Gentiles and Jews with their rulers\" echoes the conspiracy against Jesus Himself (Acts 4:27 [Pericope: Acts 4:23-31 · source: NA28], quoting Ps 2:1-2).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event takes place c. AD 47-48, during the first missionary journey of Paul and Barnabas. This chronology is established by conservative scholars like Hoehner and Bruce.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a high, arid plateau. It was a major stop on the main east-west trade route, ensuring a diverse population and a steady flow of new ideas and influences.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and, through him, to a broader Greco-Roman and Christian audience. His goal is to provide an orderly and certain account of the church's origins, demonstrating its divine power and its innocence before Roman law, despite Jewish opposition.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is carefully documenting the historical progression of the gospel, showing that the opposition it faces is not a sign of its failure, but a fulfillment of prophecy and a mark of its divine origin. The apostles' conduct provides a model for later generations of missionaries and persecuted believers.\n*   **Socio-Political Background:** As a Hellenistic city under Roman administration, Iconium had its own local magistrates or rulers (ἄρχοντες, *archontes*). This verse shows these civic leaders being drawn into the conflict, siding with the hostile elements of the Jewish and Gentile populations. This alliance of religious and secular power against the church would become a recurring feature of persecution.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The event takes place c. AD 47-48, during the first missionary journey of Paul and Barnabas. This chronology is established by conservative scholars like Hoehner and Bruce.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a high, arid plateau. It was a major stop on the main east-west trade route, ensuring a diverse population and a steady flow of new ideas and influences.</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and, through him, to a broader Greco-Roman and Christian audience. His goal is to provide an orderly and certain account of the church's origins, demonstrating its divine power and its innocence before Roman law, despite Jewish opposition.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke is carefully documenting the historical progression of the gospel, showing that the opposition it faces is not a sign of its failure, but a fulfillment of prophecy and a mark of its divine origin. The apostles' conduct provides a model for later generations of missionaries and persecuted believers.</li>\n<li><strong>Socio-Political Background:</strong> As a Hellenistic city under Roman administration, Iconium had its own local magistrates or rulers (ἄρχοντες, <em>archontes</em>). This verse shows these civic leaders being drawn into the conflict, siding with the hostile elements of the Jewish and Gentile populations. This alliance of religious and secular power against the church would become a recurring feature of persecution.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\nThis verse, though a single clause in Greek, is dense with theological and narrative weight. It marks the dangerous turning point where verbal opposition crystallizes into a murderous plot.\n\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The key is the word ὁρμή (*hormē*, \"a rush / impulse / attempt\"). This is not a formal trial or a carefully planned conspiracy, but a violent, mob-like surge of hostility. It captures the irrational fury that the gospel can provoke. The two purpose infinitives, ὑβρίσαι (*hybrisai*, \"to mistreat\") and λιθοβολῆσαι (*lithobolēsai*, \"to stone\"), reveal the plot's two-fold goal: first, public humiliation (ὕβρις, *hybris*, is about insolent shaming, not just physical harm), and second, execution by the most brutal means available.\n*   **A Unified Front:** Luke is precise about the composition of the opposition: τῶν ἐθνῶν τε καὶ Ἰουδαίων σὺν τοῖς ἄρχουσιν αὐτῶν (*tōn ethnōn te kai Ioudaiōn syn tois archousin autōn*, \"of both the Gentiles and Jews with their rulers\"). This is a terrifying coalition. The world's two great divisions (Jew and Gentile) and its power structure (the rulers) unite for one purpose: to destroy the messengers of the gospel. This alliance is a microcosm of the world system arrayed against Christ and His church, fulfilling the prophecy of Psalm 2:1-2, which Peter had already applied to the crucifixion of Jesus (Acts 4:25-27).\n*   **The Chosen Weapon:** The intent to stone (λιθοβολῆσαι, *lithobolēsai*) is significant. For the Jewish contingent, this was the prescribed punishment for blasphemy or leading Israel astray (Deut 13:6-11). They saw themselves as executing divine justice. For the Gentiles, it was simply a brutal form of mob violence. The choice of weapon reveals the religious fervor and self-righteous fury driving the opposition. This very threat would become a reality for Paul later in this journey at Lystra (Acts 14:19).\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<p>This verse, though a single clause in Greek, is dense with theological and narrative weight. It marks the dangerous turning point where verbal opposition crystallizes into a murderous plot.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The key is the word ὁρμή (<em>hormē</em>, \"a rush / impulse / attempt\"). This is not a formal trial or a carefully planned conspiracy, but a violent, mob-like surge of hostility. It captures the irrational fury that the gospel can provoke. The two purpose infinitives, ὑβρίσαι (<em>hybrisai</em>, \"to mistreat\") and λιθοβολῆσαι (<em>lithobolēsai</em>, \"to stone\"), reveal the plot's two-fold goal: first, public humiliation (ὕβρις, <em>hybris</em>, is about insolent shaming, not just physical harm), and second, execution by the most brutal means available.</li>\n<li><strong>A Unified Front:</strong> Luke is precise about the composition of the opposition: τῶν ἐθνῶν τε καὶ Ἰουδαίων σὺν τοῖς ἄρχουσιν αὐτῶν (<em>tōn ethnōn te kai Ioudaiōn syn tois archousin autōn</em>, \"of both the Gentiles and Jews with their rulers\"). This is a terrifying coalition. The world's two great divisions (Jew and Gentile) and its power structure (the rulers) unite for one purpose: to destroy the messengers of the gospel. This alliance is a microcosm of the world system arrayed against Christ and His church, fulfilling the prophecy of Psalm 2:1-2, which Peter had already applied to the crucifixion of Jesus (Acts 4:25-27).</li>\n<li><strong>The Chosen Weapon:</strong> The intent to stone (λιθοβολῆσαι, <em>lithobolēsai</em>) is significant. For the Jewish contingent, this was the prescribed punishment for blasphemy or leading Israel astray (Deut 13:6-11). They saw themselves as executing divine justice. For the Gentiles, it was simply a brutal form of mob violence. The choice of weapon reveals the religious fervor and self-righteous fury driving the opposition. This very threat would become a reality for Paul later in this journey at Lystra (Acts 14:19).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This event is a key link in the biblical motif of the persecution of God's messengers. This trajectory begins with Cain's murder of Abel (Gen 4:8), runs through the rejection of the prophets like Jeremiah (Jer 38:6) and the stoning of Zechariah (2 Chr 24:21), and finds its ultimate expression in the plot against and crucifixion of Jesus Christ (Matt 26:3-4). The apostles are now walking in their Master's footsteps (John 15:20), and their suffering is a participation in His (Col 1:24). The **Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\")** is the Cross, where the world's unified opposition achieved its apparent goal, only to be overturned by the resurrection. The hinge-of-hinges is the Cross, and the terminus verse is 2 Timothy 3:12: \"Indeed, all who desire to live a godly life in Christ Jesus will be persecuted.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** This verse defines the Church's missionary context as one of inherent conflict with the world system. The Church advances not in a neutral environment, but a hostile one.\n    *   **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"):** It demonstrates the depth of fallen humanity's rebellion, showing how religious and secular people can unite in their hatred for God's truth.\n    *   **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):** The Holy Spirit's work is implied in the apostles' awareness of the plot (v. 6, συνιδόντες, *synidontes*, \"becoming aware of it\") and their wise escape, which preserved the mission.\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis:** Conservative Christian commentators see this as a direct fulfillment of Jesus' warnings in the Gospels and a paradigm for the Church's ongoing experience. Jewish sources confirm that stoning was the legal punishment for capital religious crimes like blasphemy, illustrating the mindset of the Jewish opposition. The broader theme of the righteous fleeing from unjust plots is a staple of Jewish narrative and Midrashic reflection (e.g., David's flight from Saul), affirming that such escape is an act of prudence, not cowardice.\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ by showing his apostles sharing in His rejection. The servant is not greater than his master (John 15:20). The coalition formed against them in Iconium is a direct echo of the coalition of Herod, Pilate, the Gentiles, and the people of Israel who gathered against God's \"holy servant Jesus\" (Acts 4:27). Their suffering is a mark of their union with Him.\n",
