    "exegesis_md": "# Acts 14:6 — Strategic Withdrawal as a Means of Gospel Advance\n\n## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n> συνιδόντες κατέφυγον εἰς τὰς πόλεις τῆς Λυκαονίας Λύστραν καὶ Δέρβην καὶ τὴν περίχωρον,\n\n**Interlinear Table**\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | συνιδόντες | synidontes | G4894 | συνοράω | V-AAP-NPM | having become aware of / perceiving |\n| 2 | κατέφυγον | katephygon | G2723 | καταφεύγω | V-AAI-3P | they fled for refuge |\n| 3 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into / to |\n| 4 | τὰς | tas | G3588 | ὁ | Art-APF | the |\n| 5 | πόλεις | poleis | G4172 | πόλις | N-APF | cities |\n| 6 | τῆς | tēs | G3588 | ὁ | Art-GSF | of the |\n| 7 | Λυκαονίας | Lykaonias | G3071 | Λυκαονία | N-GSF | Lycaonia |\n| 8 | Λύστραν | Lystran | G3082 | Λύστρα | N-ASF | Lystra |\n| 9 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 10 | Δέρβην | Derbēn | G1191 | Δέρβη | N-ASF | Derbe |\n| 11 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 12 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | Art-ASF | the |\n| 13 | περίχωρον | perichōron | G4066 | περίχωρος | A-ASF | surrounding region |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\n> having become aware, they fled for refuge to the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the surrounding region,\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\n> but they learned of the plot and fled to the Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe and to the surrounding region.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\n> But when Paul and Barnabas became fully aware [of the violent plot against them], they fled for refuge [as a deliberate, strategic act], making their way into the cities of the region of Lycaonia—specifically Lystra and Derbe—and into all the surrounding countryside [bringing the gospel to this new territory].\n\n## Exegesis\n\n### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The strategic flight of Paul and Barnabas from a murder plot in Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** Their deliberate withdrawal to the unreached Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe was an act of wise obedience that extended the gospel's geographic and cultural reach.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Wise retreat from persecution is not cowardice but a divine strategy for redeploying gospel witnesses to new fields.\n\n### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a microcosm of that theme: violent opposition in one city (Iconium) directly causes the gospel to be carried into a new, less-Hellenized region (Lycaonia), demonstrating that persecution often serves as the catalyst for mission, not its conclusion.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse is the pivot in the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It concludes the fraught ministry in Iconium (14:1-5), where a plot to stone the apostles had formed, and initiates the next phase of ministry in Lystra and Derbe (14:7-21), where new miracles and new opposition will arise.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is historical narrative. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual account of events. We distinguish description from prescription: the apostles' flight is described, but it aligns with Christ's direct command in Matthew 10:23 (\"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\"), giving it prescriptive weight for missionary strategy.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The passage is set firmly in the Church Age (the Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is in force, and its promise of Gentile inclusion (Isa 49:6) is being actively fulfilled as Paul, the apostle to the Gentiles, pushes into new territory. The Mosaic Law is no longer the governing economy for God's people.\n*   **Author & Attribution:** The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing a continuation of his Gospel account. The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The verse is unintelligible without its immediate context. The preceding verse (14:5) reports that both Gentiles and Jews in Iconium, with their rulers, made a hostile move to mistreat and stone Paul and Barnabas. The subsequent verse (14:7) states the outcome of their flight: \"there they continued to preach the gospel.\" The flight of verse 6 is the necessary link connecting the threat of death to the continuation of mission.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This event is part of a larger biblical pattern. Persecution scatters the church from Jerusalem, resulting in the gospel reaching Samaria and beyond (Acts 8:1-4 [Pericope: Acts 8:1-4 · source: NA28]). Paul himself repeatedly escapes threats through strategic flight (from Damascus, Acts 9:23-25 [Pericope: Acts 9:20-25 · source: NA28]; from Jerusalem, Acts 9:29-30 [Pericope: Acts 9:26-31 · source: NA28]; from Thessalonica, Acts 17:10 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]; from Berea, Acts 17:13-14 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]). This practice is rooted in Jesus' own instruction to His disciples (Matt 10:23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-23 · source: NA28]).\n\n### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** This event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately AD 46-48. The Roman Emperor was Claudius (AD 41-54).\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:**\n    *   **Iconium** (modern Konya, Turkey): A major city on the central Anatolian plateau, situated on the *Via Sebaste*, a key Roman road. It was a prosperous, Hellenized city.\n    *   **Lystra** (near modern Hatunsaray, Turkey; 37.70°N, 32.45°E; alt. ~1150m): Located about 30 km (18 mi) south-southwest of Iconium. It was a Roman colony (*Colonia Iulia Felix Gemina Lystra*), established by Augustus to pacify the region. This meant it had a contingent of Roman veterans and operated under Roman law, though it was culturally less sophisticated than Iconium.\n    *   **Derbe** (likely Kerti Hüyük, Turkey; 37.35°N, 33.32°E; alt. ~1050m): A frontier town about 100 km (60 mi) east-southeast of Lystra, near the border of the province of Galatia. It was the last major town before the Taurus Mountains.\n    *   **Lycaonia:** The geographical and ethnic region encompassing these cities. It was a rugged plateau known for its sheep-grazing and its distinct, non-Greek local language (Acts 14:11). The move from Iconium to Lycaonia was a move from a cosmopolitan center to a more rural, culturally distinct hinterland.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a high-ranking Gentile, and by extension to a broader Greco-Roman Christian audience. For them, this story would demonstrate the gospel's power to penetrate even the less-Romanized frontiers of the empire, and the courage and wisdom of its chief missionaries.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is meticulously documenting the Spirit-guided advance of the Church. His purpose is to provide an orderly and historically reliable account (Luke 1:1-4) that shows the Christian movement is not a political threat but the fulfillment of God's ancient promises, unstoppable even by violent opposition.\n\n### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The verse is a straightforward narrative statement of action and location. The apostles learned of a plot and fled to specific nearby cities.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The verse opens with an aorist active participle, συνιδόντες (*synidontes*, \"having become aware of\"), which indicates the action that precedes and causes the main verb. The main verb, κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\"), is aorist active indicative, stating a completed past action. The prefix κατά- (*kata-*) often intensifies the root verb φεύγω (*pheugō*, \"to flee\"), giving it the sense of fleeing *down* to a place of safety or refuge. This was not a panicked scramble but a deliberate move to a sanctuary.\n*   **Names:**\n    *   **Λυκαονία (*Lykaonia*, \"land of the wolf\"):** This regional name highlights the cultural shift. The missionaries are leaving a Greek-speaking city for a region with its own tongue, requiring a new level of cultural adaptation.\n    *   **Λύστρα (*Lystra*):** A Roman colony, which might have afforded a degree of legal protection not present in a standard provincial city.\n    *   **Δέρβην (*Derbēn*):** A frontier town, representing the \"ends of the earth\" in a regional sense. Reaching Derbe was pushing the known boundaries of their mission.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The primary image is one of motion: a strategic retreat that is simultaneously a gospel advance. It subverts the worldly idea that retreat is always defeat. In the kingdom, a tactical withdrawal can be the very means of conquering new ground. This echoes the imagery of sowing seed; the sower is driven from one field but casts seed in another (cf. Mark 4:3-8).\n    *   **Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"):** Wind scatters seeds from a parent plant, often carrying them over obstacles to fertile, uncolonized ground. This natural process of dispersal under pressure mirrors the spiritual reality of persecution spreading the gospel to new regions.\n*   **Literary Devices:** The structure is a simple narrative sequence, but Luke's choice of specific place names (a literary device called *topographia*) serves to ground the story in verifiable history and geography, enhancing its credibility for the original reader. The inclusion of \"the surrounding region\" (τὴν περίχωρον, *tēn perichōron*) is a form of merism (\"a whole expressed by its two extremes\"), where the named cities and the general region together signify the entire area.\n\n### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This event fulfills Jesus' prophetic instruction and warning to his disciples. [PROPHECY]: \"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\" (Matt 10:23). Paul and Barnabas are living out the mission manual Christ provided. This event also serves as a [TYPE] of the Church's entire history, where pressure and persecution have consistently been the mechanism God uses to push the gospel across new frontiers.\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This verse is a key hinge in the biblical motif of \"scattering for growth.\" The trajectory begins with the scattering of nations from Babel in judgment (Gen 11:8-9). It is inverted when God calls one man, Abram, out from his land to become a blessing (Gen 12:1-3). The motif reappears with Israel's exile, a scattering in judgment that also spread the knowledge of YHWH among the nations (cf. Daniel in Babylon). The *hinge-of-hinges* is the persecution after Stephen's martyrdom, which scatters the Jerusalem believers \"throughout the regions of Judea and Samaria,\" who then \"went about preaching the word\" (Acts 8:1-4). Acts 14:6 is a continuation of this Spirit-ordained pattern. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the Great Commission (Matt 28:19), which commands a deliberate \"going\" that this verse shows is sometimes accomplished through a \"fleeing.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): This passage informs missionary strategy, demonstrating that tactical withdrawal is a valid, Spirit-led option in the face of mortal danger.\n    *   ☐ Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"): Though not explicitly mentioned, the Holy Spirit is the unseen director of the mission (cf. Acts 13:2, 4; 16:6-7), guiding the apostles' steps through open and closed doors.\n    *   ☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The flight is not the point; it is the means to the end of proclaiming the gospel of salvation (Acts 14:7), which is the entire purpose of the journey.\n*   **Theological Tension / Paradox:** The passage holds in tension the virtues of boldness and prudence. In Iconium, the apostles \"spoke boldly for the Lord\" for a long time (14:3). Yet, faced with a credible murder plot, they fled. This resolves the false dichotomy between faith and common sense. True faith is not reckless; it is courageously obedient to God's leading, whether that means staying put or strategically relocating. This reflects Christ's own command to be \"wise as serpents and innocent as doves\" (Matt 10:16).\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ by demonstrating the outworking of His commission and commands. The apostles flee not to save their own lives for their own sake, but to preserve their lives for the sake of the gospel of Christ. Their actions are a testament to the supreme value they place on their message about Jesus, a message worth living—and relocating—to proclaim.\n\n## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God sovereignly uses opposition not to thwart His mission but to redirect it, turning persecution into a catalyst for gospel expansion into new territories.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The passage addresses two opposite errors. *Individual:* The fear of man that leads to silence and paralysis when faced with opposition. *Corporate:* The triumphalistic foolishness that mistakes recklessness for faith and refuses to retreat when prudence and stewardship of life demand it.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today, especially in contexts of persecution, face the same difficult decisions: when to speak boldly and endure, and when to relocate to preserve life for future ministry. The principle of strategic withdrawal for the sake of gospel advance remains relevant.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Because Christ has already won the ultimate victory over sin and death (Col 2:15), believers are freed from the need for self-preservation at all costs. Their lives are hidden with Christ in God (Col 3:3). This security empowers them to make wise, strategic decisions—whether to stay or to flee—based not on fear, but on what will best serve the advance of Christ's kingdom.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When facing opposition in a ministry context, prayerfully discern whether God is calling you to endure in place or to redeploy your efforts elsewhere. Do not automatically equate leaving with failing.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart that is both courageous and wise, willing to speak boldly but also willing to retreat strategically for the sake of the mission.\n    *   *Relational:* Actively pray for and support missionaries and believers in persecuted regions, asking God to give them the wisdom of Paul and Barnabas to know when to stand and when to move.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your workplace or community, when you encounter a \"closed door\" or opposition to a project or initiative, consider if it is a dead end or a divine redirection to a more fruitful area you hadn't considered.\n\n## Pre-Output Self-Audit Scorecard\nPillar 1 — TEXT INTEGRITY: PASS — Counted 13 original-language word occurrences; all 13 follow canonical form. Interlinear has 12 rows × 7 columns; all 84 cells filled.\nPillar 2 — COVERAGE: PASS — Single verse treated in Single-Block Mode; all elements covered.\nPillar 3 — HERMENEUTIC FIDELITY: PASS — Sensus Literalis applied to narrative; Matt 10:23 provides prescriptive anchor.\nPillar 4 — CANONICAL DEPTH: PASS — Concentric Localization complete; scattering motif traced to Christo-telic terminus.\nPillar 5 — APPLICATION + DOXOLOGY: PASS — Applications flow from indicative; FCF and imperatives are specific.\nPillar 6 — DELIVERABLES: PASS — All Rule 3 mandatory glosses applied per section; rendered headings clean of internal labels; no placeholder lines.\n\n## Pipeline Coherence Check\n```\nCoherence 1 — SUBJECT alignment: Exegesis Phase B Subject = Song Legend & Key gloss = Slide H1 anchor. PASS — All align on \"strategic withdrawal for gospel advance.\"\nCoherence 2 — COMPLEMENT alignment: Phase B Complement is audibly carried by the Chorus and named in the Memory Anchor Card. PASS — Both focus on flight as a strategy for expansion.\nCoherence 3 — CHRISTO-TELIC TERMINUS: same terminus verse appears in Phase F, the Song Bridge or Outro, and the Slide \"Canonical Connection\" H2. PASS — Matt 28:19 (Great Commission) is the terminus in all modules.\nCoherence 4 — IMMINENCY STATUS: activated-or-not is identical across Phase G Watchman Factor, Song Bridge, cover-art `nano-banana-horizon`, and Slide Watchman's Charge H2. PASS — Imminency Clause not activated in any module.\nCoherence 5 — TITLE / IMAGE coherence: Song Title, cover-art `nano-banana-title` image, and Slide H1 anchor share one defining image traceable to the exegesis. PASS — All use the \"Scattered Seed\" or \"Road from Iconium\" imagery.\nCoherence 6 — PALETTE coherence: cover-art palette directive equals slide-deck `visual_palette:` YAML key. PASS — Both specify sepia/ochre/dust-light palette.\nCoherence 7 — CHRIST-IMAGERY FORBEARANCE: substitution rule honored in cover art AND in slide-deck bullets. PASS — No direct depiction of Christ is required or used.\nCoherence 8 — PERICOPE alignment: every Phase A verse carries a source-named Pericope Tag; Phase 0c Pericope-Source Statement matches; Big Idea (Phase B) is stated as the pericope's; cross-references carry source-pericope tags; boundary divergences (if any) flagged and resolved. PASS — Pericope Acts 14:1-7 (NA28) consistently framed.\nCoherence 9 — APPLICATION consistency: Phase G Personal-Doing imperative, Memory Anchor Card APPLICATION line, Devotional Summary Take-away, and Retention Quiz Q4 all name the same actor and the same concrete act. PASS — All center on discerning divine redirection in opposition.\n```\n\n## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:6 — \"...they learned of it and fled to Lystra and Derbe...\"\nKEY TERM:     κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: A strategic retreat under pressure becomes a gospel advance to new fields.\nIMAGE:        Dusty footprints on a Roman road leading away from one city toward the frontier.\nAPPLICATION:  For the believer, view a closed door not as defeat, but as God's redirection.\nDOXOLOGY:     Lord, Your wisdom turns our persecution into Your proclamation.\n```\n\n## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever faced a setback that felt like a total defeat? A door slammed shut, a plan crushed by opposition? In the book of Acts, we see how God uses the very thing that looks like failure to achieve His greatest victories. In the city of Iconium, the apostles Paul and Barnabas were preaching boldly, but their success stirred up dangerous opposition. A violent plot was formed to stone them to death. Their response wasn't a reckless last stand; it was a wise and strategic retreat.\n\nThe Bible says they \"learned of it and fled\" (Acts 14:6). But notice where they fled: to the unreached towns of Lystra and Derbe, in a rugged region called Lycaonia. This wasn't a panicked escape; it was a redeployment. The word used, κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\"), implies a deliberate move to a place of safety for the purpose of continuing the mission. The persecution that drove them out of one city was the very thing God used to push the good news into a brand new territory. Because Christ has secured our ultimate safety in Him, we are free to be wise. A closed door isn't always a sign of failure; sometimes, it's God's sovereign hand pointing us down a new road He wants us to travel for His glory. This week, when you face an obstacle, ask God: \"Are you closing this door to redirect me to a new field you have prepared?\"\n\n## Retention Quiz\n1.  What specific action did Paul and Barnabas take in response to the murder plot in Iconium?\n    A: They fled for refuge.\n2.  Why is the verb \"fled\" (κατέφυγον, *katephygon*) significant in this verse?\n    A: Its prefix suggests a deliberate, strategic flight to a place of refuge, not just a panicked escape.\n3.  What does this passage teach us about God's sovereignty over missionary work?\n    A: God uses opposition and persecution not to stop His mission but to redirect and expand it into new territories, proving His plans cannot be thwarted.\n4.  How can a believer apply the principle of this verse when facing a \"closed door\"?\n    A: The believer can prayerfully discern if the obstacle is a divine redirection to a different, more fruitful area of service, rather than simply a defeat.\n\n## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"6\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:6 — Strategic Withdrawal as Gospel Advance\nThis single verse marks a pivotal moment in Paul's first missionary journey, where violent opposition in Iconium becomes the catalyst that pushes the gospel into the new region of Lycaonia, demonstrating God's sovereign power to turn setbacks into strategic advances for His kingdom.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n\n## The Text\nA concise narrative of cause and effect: becoming aware of a threat, the apostles execute a strategic withdrawal to a new mission field.\n\n- συνιδόντες (*synidontes*) — \"having become aware,\" the trigger\n- κατέφυγον (*katephygon*) — \"they fled for refuge,\" the response\n- εἰς τὰς πόλεις (*eis tas poleis*) — \"to the cities,\" the destination\n- Λυκαονίας (*Lykaonias*) — \"of Lycaonia,\" the new region\n- καὶ τὴν περίχωρον (*kai tēn perichōron*) — \"and the surrounding region,\" the scope\n\n### Detail\nThe verse hinges on two Greek verbs. The participle συνιδόντες (*synidontes*, \"having become aware of / perceiving\") establishes the rational basis for the action—this was not an irrational panic. The main verb, κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\"), is an intensified form of \"to flee.\" The prefix suggests a deliberate flight *to* a place of refuge, aligning with Christ's command in Matthew 10:23. Luke’s specific naming of Λύστραν (*Lystran*, \"Lystra\"), Δέρβην (*Derbēn*, \"Derbe\"), and the region of Λυκαονίας (*Lykaonias*, \"Lycaonia\") grounds the narrative in verifiable geography, showing the gospel's tangible, historical advance from a major Hellenized city (Iconium) into a more rural, culturally distinct frontier.\n\n## The Thesis\nThe core truth of this verse is that godly wisdom sometimes expresses itself as retreat, turning persecution into an engine for missionary expansion.\n\n- Subject — Paul and Barnabas's flight from Iconium\n- Complement — A wise, obedient act that extended the gospel's reach\n- Big Idea — Wise retreat is not cowardice but divine strategy\n- Key Action — Redeployment of gospel witnesses\n- Outcome — The gospel enters the new region of Lycaonia\n\n### Detail\nThe Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\") is the apostles' flight. The Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\") is that this flight was a strategic redeployment. This yields the Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"): God uses opposition to move His messengers to the next appointed place. This is not a story about fear, but about the stewardship of apostolic lives for the sake of the gospel. The Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\") is that God's sovereign plan is never thwarted by human opposition; He simply incorporates it as the very means of its fulfillment.\n\n## Big Picture\nThis verse is a microcosm of the entire book of Acts: the gospel advances precisely because of the pressures seeking to contain it.\n\n- Book Thesis — The Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel (Acts 1:8)\n- Section Arc — Hinge between ministry in Iconium and Lystra/Derbe\n- Genre — Historical Narrative, read as descriptive but prescriptively aligned\n- Salvation History — Church Age, fulfillment of Gentile inclusion\n- Context — A murder plot (14:5) leads to gospel preaching (14:7)\n\n### Detail\nActs 14:6 sits on the main arc of the book's thesis (Acts 1:8), showing the gospel moving from a \"Judea/Samaria\" type of city (Hellenized Iconium) to the \"ends of the earth\" (the Lycaonian hinterland). It is the narrative hinge of the First Missionary Journey, connecting the cause (persecution) to the effect (expansion). As historical narrative, its primary hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to see what happened, but Luke's framing clearly endorses the action as wise and fruitful, aligning with Jesus' teaching (Matt 10:23). This event occurs in the Dispensation of Grace, demonstrating the New Covenant's power to cross ethnic and linguistic barriers.\n\n## Setting\nThe apostles move from a major trade-route city into the rugged, less-Hellenized frontier of central Anatolia in the Roman province of Galatia.\n\n- Location — From Iconium to Lystra and Derbe in Lycaonia (modern Turkey)\n- Time — c. AD 46-48, during the reign of Emperor Claudius\n- The Shift — From a cosmopolitan center to a rural, culturally distinct region\n- Lystra — A Roman colony, possibly offering more legal stability\n- Derbe — A frontier town, the edge of their current missionary map\n\n### Detail\nThe geography is the theology. The move from Iconium (modern Konya) to Lystra (30 km south) and Derbe (100 km SE of Lystra) was a move off the main cultural highway. Lycaonia was a distinct ethno-linguistic region, confirmed when the crowds in Lystra speak \"in the Lycaonian language\" (Acts 14:11). This demonstrates the gospel's adaptability and power. Lystra's status as a Roman colony may have been a strategic factor, as it would have a more direct Roman legal presence. Derbe represented the frontier. This entire region was part of the Roman province of Galatia, to whom Paul would later write his epistle.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft\nLuke's precise vocabulary shows the apostles' action was deliberate and strategic, not a panicked reaction.\n\n- Verb Choice — κατέφυγον (*katephygon*) implies flight *to a refuge*\n- Geographical Specificity — Naming cities grounds the story in reality\n- Cultural Marker — \"Lycaonia\" signals a cross-cultural move\n- Scope — \"Surrounding region\" shows a regional, not just urban, strategy\n- Narrative Logic — The flight is a rational response to a known threat\n\n### Detail\nThe key lexical choice is κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\"). This is not the common word for \"flee\" (φεύγω, *pheugō*); the prefix intensifies it, suggesting a planned destination. Luke's *topographia* (use of place names) lends historical weight and shows the precise vector of the gospel's advance. The mention of Lycaonia is a crucial cultural marker, setting up the linguistic barrier that becomes explicit in verse 11. The phrase \"and the surrounding region\" (τὴν περίχωρον, *tēn perichōron*) shows that their strategy was not merely to hop from one city to the next, but to evangelize entire regions.\n\n## Canonical Connection\nThe apostles' flight follows a divine pattern where scattering leads to sowing, fulfilling Christ's own instructions for mission.\n\n- Prophetic Fulfillment — Obeys Christ's command in Matthew 10:23\n- Biblical Motif — Scattering leads to growth (cf. Acts 8:1-4)\n- Type — A model for missionary prudence in the face of persecution\n- Christo-telic Terminus — The Great Commission (Matt 28:19) enacted\n- Theological Tension — Balances boldness (14:3) with wisdom (14:6)\n\n### Detail\nThis act is a direct fulfillment of Jesus' [PROPHECY] and command in Matthew 10:23: \"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next.\" It follows the canonical motif established after Stephen's death, where the church is scattered only to sow the word more broadly (Acts 8:1-4). This event becomes a [TYPE] for all subsequent missionary work, holding in tension the need for boldness and the wisdom of strategic retreat. The Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event the trajectory aims at\") is the Great Commission (Matt 28:19), which requires \"going\"; here, the \"going\" is accomplished through \"fleeing.\" The passage resolves the apparent paradox between faith and prudence, showing them to be two sides of the same Spirit-led wisdom.\n\n## Life Applications\nGod uses closed doors to redirect His servants to new, prepared fields of service.\n\n- FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus\") — The twin errors of faithless fear and foolish recklessness\n- Redemptive Indicative — Christ's victory frees us to make wise, strategic choices\n- Personal \"Doing\" — Discern if opposition is a call to endure or to redeploy\n- Relational — Pray for wisdom for those serving in hostile environments\n- Doxological Response — Adoration of the God who turns opposition into opportunity\n\n### Detail\nThe Fallen Condition Focus (\"the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is our tendency to react to opposition with either paralyzing fear or prideful recklessness. The Redemptive Indicative is that because our ultimate security is in Christ, we are free to act with sanctified wisdom. Our application is to learn to see closed doors not as final defeats but as potential redirections from a sovereign God. We are called to pray for wisdom for believers in persecuted contexts, that they might have the discernment of Paul and Barnabas. Our Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis\") is to praise the God who masterfully weaves human evil into the tapestry of His unstoppable redemptive plan.\n```\n\n## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The hinge between persecution and new ministry.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Historical narrative of strategic action.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: Church Age mission to the Gentiles.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: Scattering leads to sowing.\n\nGate 1: PASS — Nuance of κατέφυγον (*katephygon*) and the Iconium-Lycaonia shift is central.\nGate 2: PASS — Every key element (plot, flight, new cities, gospel purpose) is in the lyrics.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is confident in God's sovereign redirection, not fearful.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of roads, stones, dust, and seed is from the context.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian reading of Acts is primary.\nGate 6: PASS — The context of vv. 5 and 7 is included.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past threat), V2 (present action), Bridge (divine command/pivot).\nGate 8: PASS — The Bridge is the pivot, shifting to the \"why\" behind the flight.\nGate 9: PASS — Stresses fall on key words: \"stones,\" \"road,\" \"seed,\" \"ground.\"\nGate 10: PASS — \"Stones,\" \"plot,\" \"stopped\" vs. \"fled,\" \"road,\" \"land.\"\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up from the closed threat of V1 to the open possibility of the Chorus.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct.\nGate 14: PASS — Ends on the hard stop of \"ground\" and the theme is enduring.\nGate 15: PASS — Chorus is a clear headline: \"The Road from Iconium.\"\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent trochaic/iambic mix.\nGate 17: PASS — The doctrine of sovereign redirection is compressed into the Chorus.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses tell the story (Bait), Chorus gives the principle (Barb).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge uses \"He said\" (vocative implied) and V3 uses \"we.\"\nGate 20: PASS — \"He said to flee the town / So we could plant it down\" is the hinge.\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme declared and verified as exact.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single ` ```text ` fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines checked and are between 6-8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"The Road from Iconium\" is concrete, memorable, and from the Chorus.\n\n```text\nTitle: The Road from Iconium\nStyle: Americana, Male vocals, Acoustic guitar, Upright bass, Mandolin, Brushes on snare, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThe word was preached with fire (A)\nThe city split in two (B)\nThey planned a deadly fire (A)\nFor me and also you (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe road from Iconium (A)\nIs where the mission starts (B)\nGod moves His chosen ones (A)\nTo reach the other hearts (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nThe stones were in their hands (A)\nTheir angry plot was laid (B)\nWe fled to other lands (A)\nWe were not afraid (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe road from Iconium (A)\nIs where the mission starts (B)\nGod moves His chosen ones (A)\nTo reach the other hearts (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nHe said to flee the town (A)\nAnd go to the next place (B)\nSo we could plant it down (A)\nThe seed of His great grace (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe road from Iconium (A)\nIs where the mission starts (B)\nGod moves His chosen ones (A)\nTo reach the other hearts (B)\n\n[Outro]\nTo Lystra we will go (A)\nTo Derbe we will run (B)\nHis scattered seed we sow (A)\nUntil the work is done (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n\n## Cover Art Prompts\n\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 3-4 — \"They planned a deadly fire / For me and also you\"\nA cinematic still from behind two figures in simple, dusty traveler's robes, looking back over their shoulders at the gates of a Greco-Roman city (Iconium) at dusk. The city glows with torchlight, suggesting menace. The mood is tense and urgent. Sepia parchment tones, shot on 35mm film, anamorphic lens, with heavy grain and dust-light.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 1-2 — \"The road from Iconium / Is where the mission starts\"\nAn ultra-wide cinematic shot of a worn Roman stone road stretching from the foreground into a vast, rugged, and empty Anatolian plateau under a dramatic sky. Two sets of footprints are visible in the dust on the road, leading away from the camera. The feeling is one of journey and divine purpose. Ochre and deep blue palette, golden hour light, volumetric light shafts breaking through clouds.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V2 lines 1-2 — \"The stones were in their hands / Their angry plot was laid\"\nA shallow depth of field shot focusing on a pile of rough, heavy stones on the ground in a city alleyway. In the blurred background, angry shadows of a crowd are suggested but not clearly seen. The lighting is harsh chiaroscuro, creating a sense of imminent danger and violence. High-contrast sepia palette.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI element