      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The strategic flight of Paul and Barnabas from a murder plot in Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** Their deliberate withdrawal to the unreached Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe was an act of wise obedience that extended the gospel's geographic and cultural reach.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Wise retreat from persecution is not cowardice but a divine strategy for redeploying gospel witnesses to new fields.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The strategic flight of Paul and Barnabas from a murder plot in Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> Their deliberate withdrawal to the unreached Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe was an act of wise obedience that extended the gospel's geographic and cultural reach.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Wise retreat from persecution is not cowardice but a divine strategy for redeploying gospel witnesses to new fields.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a microcosm of that theme: violent opposition in one city (Iconium) directly causes the gospel to be carried into a new, less-Hellenized region (Lycaonia), demonstrating that persecution often serves as the catalyst for mission, not its conclusion.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse is the pivot in the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It concludes the fraught ministry in Iconium (14:1-5), where a plot to stone the apostles had formed, and initiates the next phase of ministry in Lystra and Derbe (14:7-21), where new miracles and new opposition will arise.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is historical narrative. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual account of events. We distinguish description from prescription: the apostles' flight is described, but it aligns with Christ's direct command in Matthew 10:23 (\"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\"), giving it prescriptive weight for missionary strategy.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The passage is set firmly in the Church Age (the Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is in force, and its promise of Gentile inclusion (Isa 49:6) is being actively fulfilled as Paul, the apostle to the Gentiles, pushes into new territory. The Mosaic Law is no longer the governing economy for God's people.\n*   **Author & Attribution:** The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing a continuation of his Gospel account. The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The verse is unintelligible without its immediate context. The preceding verse (14:5) reports that both Gentiles and Jews in Iconium, with their rulers, made a hostile move to mistreat and stone Paul and Barnabas. The subsequent verse (14:7) states the outcome of their flight: \"there they continued to preach the gospel.\" The flight of verse 6 is the necessary link connecting the threat of death to the continuation of mission.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This event is part of a larger biblical pattern. Persecution scatters the church from Jerusalem, resulting in the gospel reaching Samaria and beyond (Acts 8:1-4 [Pericope: Acts 8:1-4 · source: NA28]). Paul himself repeatedly escapes threats through strategic flight (from Damascus, Acts 9:23-25 [Pericope: Acts 9:20-25 · source: NA28]; from Jerusalem, Acts 9:29-30 [Pericope: Acts 9:26-31 · source: NA28]; from Thessalonica, Acts 17:10 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]; from Berea, Acts 17:13-14 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]). This practice is rooted in Jesus' own instruction to His disciples (Matt 10:23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-23 · source: NA28]).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a microcosm of that theme: violent opposition in one city (Iconium) directly causes the gospel to be carried into a new, less-Hellenized region (Lycaonia), demonstrating that persecution often serves as the catalyst for mission, not its conclusion.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse is the pivot in the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It concludes the fraught ministry in Iconium (14:1-5), where a plot to stone the apostles had formed, and initiates the next phase of ministry in Lystra and Derbe (14:7-21), where new miracles and new opposition will arise.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic:</strong> The genre is historical narrative. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual account of events. We distinguish description from prescription: the apostles' flight is described, but it aligns with Christ's direct command in Matthew 10:23 (\"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\"), giving it prescriptive weight for missionary strategy.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> The passage is set firmly in the Church Age (the Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is in force, and its promise of Gentile inclusion (Isa 49:6) is being actively fulfilled as Paul, the apostle to the Gentiles, pushes into new territory. The Mosaic Law is no longer the governing economy for God's people.</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing a continuation of his Gospel account. The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The verse is unintelligible without its immediate context. The preceding verse (14:5) reports that both Gentiles and Jews in Iconium, with their rulers, made a hostile move to mistreat and stone Paul and Barnabas. The subsequent verse (14:7) states the outcome of their flight: \"there they continued to preach the gospel.\" The flight of verse 6 is the necessary link connecting the threat of death to the continuation of mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This event is part of a larger biblical pattern. Persecution scatters the church from Jerusalem, resulting in the gospel reaching Samaria and beyond (Acts 8:1-4 [Pericope: Acts 8:1-4 · source: NA28]). Paul himself repeatedly escapes threats through strategic flight (from Damascus, Acts 9:23-25 [Pericope: Acts 9:20-25 · source: NA28]; from Jerusalem, Acts 9:29-30 [Pericope: Acts 9:26-31 · source: NA28]; from Thessalonica, Acts 17:10 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]; from Berea, Acts 17:13-14 [Pericope: Acts 17:10-15 · source: NA28]). This practice is rooted in Jesus' own instruction to His disciples (Matt 10:23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-23 · source: NA28]).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** This event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately AD 46-48. The Roman Emperor was Claudius (AD 41-54).\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:**\n    *   **Iconium** (modern Konya, Turkey): A major city on the central Anatolian plateau, situated on the *Via Sebaste*, a key Roman road. It was a prosperous, Hellenized city.\n    *   **Lystra** (near modern Hatunsaray, Turkey; 37.70°N, 32.45°E; alt. ~1150m): Located about 30 km (18 mi) south-southwest of Iconium. It was a Roman colony (*Colonia Iulia Felix Gemina Lystra*), established by Augustus to pacify the region. This meant it had a contingent of Roman veterans and operated under Roman law, though it was culturally less sophisticated than Iconium.\n    *   **Derbe** (likely Kerti Hüyük, Turkey; 37.35°N, 33.32°E; alt. ~1050m): A frontier town about 100 km (60 mi) east-southeast of Lystra, near the border of the province of Galatia. It was the last major town before the Taurus Mountains.\n    *   **Lycaonia:** The geographical and ethnic region encompassing these cities. It was a rugged plateau known for its sheep-grazing and its distinct, non-Greek local language (Acts 14:11). The move from Iconium to Lycaonia was a move from a cosmopolitan center to a more rural, culturally distinct hinterland.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a high-ranking Gentile, and by extension to a broader Greco-Roman Christian audience. For them, this story would demonstrate the gospel's power to penetrate even the less-Romanized frontiers of the empire, and the courage and wisdom of its chief missionaries.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is meticulously documenting the Spirit-guided advance of the Church. His purpose is to provide an orderly and historically reliable account (Luke 1:1-4) that shows the Christian movement is not a political threat but the fulfillment of God's ancient promises, unstoppable even by violent opposition.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> This event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately AD 46-48. The Roman Emperor was Claudius (AD 41-54).</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong><ul>\n<li><strong>Iconium</strong> (modern Konya, Turkey): A major city on the central Anatolian plateau, situated on the <em>Via Sebaste</em>, a key Roman road. It was a prosperous, Hellenized city.</li>\n<li><strong>Lystra</strong> (near modern Hatunsaray, Turkey; 37.70°N, 32.45°E; alt. ~1150m): Located about 30 km (18 mi) south-southwest of Iconium. It was a Roman colony (<em>Colonia Iulia Felix Gemina Lystra</em>), established by Augustus to pacify the region. This meant it had a contingent of Roman veterans and operated under Roman law, though it was culturally less sophisticated than Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Derbe</strong> (likely Kerti Hüyük, Turkey; 37.35°N, 33.32°E; alt. ~1050m): A frontier town about 100 km (60 mi) east-southeast of Lystra, near the border of the province of Galatia. It was the last major town before the Taurus Mountains.</li>\n<li><strong>Lycaonia:</strong> The geographical and ethnic region encompassing these cities. It was a rugged plateau known for its sheep-grazing and its distinct, non-Greek local language (Acts 14:11). The move from Iconium to Lycaonia was a move from a cosmopolitan center to a more rural, culturally distinct hinterland.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a high-ranking Gentile, and by extension to a broader Greco-Roman Christian audience. For them, this story would demonstrate the gospel's power to penetrate even the less-Romanized frontiers of the empire, and the courage and wisdom of its chief missionaries.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke is meticulously documenting the Spirit-guided advance of the Church. His purpose is to provide an orderly and historically reliable account (Luke 1:1-4) that shows the Christian movement is not a political threat but the fulfillment of God's ancient promises, unstoppable even by violent opposition.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The verse is a straightforward narrative statement of action and location. The apostles learned of a plot and fled to specific nearby cities.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The verse opens with an aorist active participle, συνιδόντες (*synidontes*, \"having become aware of\"), which indicates the action that precedes and causes the main verb. The main verb, κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\"), is aorist active indicative, stating a completed past action. The prefix κατά- (*kata-*) often intensifies the root verb φεύγω (*pheugō*, \"to flee\"), giving it the sense of fleeing *down* to a place of safety or refuge. This was not a panicked scramble but a deliberate move to a sanctuary.\n*   **Names:**\n    *   **Λυκαονία (*Lykaonia*, \"land of the wolf\"):** This regional name highlights the cultural shift. The missionaries are leaving a Greek-speaking city for a region with its own tongue, requiring a new level of cultural adaptation.\n    *   **Λύστρα (*Lystra*):** A Roman colony, which might have afforded a degree of legal protection not present in a standard provincial city.\n    *   **Δέρβην (*Derbēn*):** A frontier town, representing the \"ends of the earth\" in a regional sense. Reaching Derbe was pushing the known boundaries of their mission.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The primary image is one of motion: a strategic retreat that is simultaneously a gospel advance. It subverts the worldly idea that retreat is always defeat. In the kingdom, a tactical withdrawal can be the very means of conquering new ground. This echoes the imagery of sowing seed; the sower is driven from one field but casts seed in another (cf. Mark 4:3-8).\n    *   **Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"):** Wind scatters seeds from a parent plant, often carrying them over obstacles to fertile, uncolonized ground. This natural process of dispersal under pressure mirrors the spiritual reality of persecution spreading the gospel to new regions.\n*   **Literary Devices:** The structure is a simple narrative sequence, but Luke's choice of specific place names (a literary device called *topographia*) serves to ground the story in verifiable history and geography, enhancing its credibility for the original reader. The inclusion of \"the surrounding region\" (τὴν περίχωρον, *tēn perichōron*) is a form of merism (\"a whole expressed by its two extremes\"), where the named cities and the general region together signify the entire area.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter:</strong> The verse is a straightforward narrative statement of action and location. The apostles learned of a plot and fled to specific nearby cities.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The verse opens with an aorist active participle, συνιδόντες (<em>synidontes</em>, \"having become aware of\"), which indicates the action that precedes and causes the main verb. The main verb, κατέφυγον (<em>katephygon</em>, \"they fled for refuge\"), is aorist active indicative, stating a completed past action. The prefix κατά- (<em>kata-</em>) often intensifies the root verb φεύγω (<em>pheugō</em>, \"to flee\"), giving it the sense of fleeing <em>down</em> to a place of safety or refuge. This was not a panicked scramble but a deliberate move to a sanctuary.</li>\n<li><strong>Names:</strong><ul>\n<li><strong>Λυκαονία (<em>Lykaonia</em>, \"land of the wolf\"):</strong> This regional name highlights the cultural shift. The missionaries are leaving a Greek-speaking city for a region with its own tongue, requiring a new level of cultural adaptation.</li>\n<li><strong>Λύστρα (<em>Lystra</em>):</strong> A Roman colony, which might have afforded a degree of legal protection not present in a standard provincial city.</li>\n<li><strong>Δέρβην (<em>Derbēn</em>):</strong> A frontier town, representing the \"ends of the earth\" in a regional sense. Reaching Derbe was pushing the known boundaries of their mission.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):</strong> The primary image is one of motion: a strategic retreat that is simultaneously a gospel advance. It subverts the worldly idea that retreat is always defeat. In the kingdom, a tactical withdrawal can be the very means of conquering new ground. This echoes the imagery of sowing seed; the sower is driven from one field but casts seed in another (cf. Mark 4:3-8).<ul>\n<li><strong>Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"):</strong> Wind scatters seeds from a parent plant, often carrying them over obstacles to fertile, uncolonized ground. This natural process of dispersal under pressure mirrors the spiritual reality of persecution spreading the gospel to new regions.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Literary Devices:</strong> The structure is a simple narrative sequence, but Luke's choice of specific place names (a literary device called <em>topographia</em>) serves to ground the story in verifiable history and geography, enhancing its credibility for the original reader. The inclusion of \"the surrounding region\" (τὴν περίχωρον, <em>tēn perichōron</em>) is a form of merism (\"a whole expressed by its two extremes\"), where the named cities and the general region together signify the entire area.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This event fulfills Jesus' prophetic instruction and warning to his disciples. [PROPHECY]: \"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\" (Matt 10:23). Paul and Barnabas are living out the mission manual Christ provided. This event also serves as a [TYPE] of the Church's entire history, where pressure and persecution have consistently been the mechanism God uses to push the gospel across new frontiers.\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This verse is a key hinge in the biblical motif of \"scattering for growth.\" The trajectory begins with the scattering of nations from Babel in judgment (Gen 11:8-9). It is inverted when God calls one man, Abram, out from his land to become a blessing (Gen 12:1-3). The motif reappears with Israel's exile, a scattering in judgment that also spread the knowledge of YHWH among the nations (cf. Daniel in Babylon). The *hinge-of-hinges* is the persecution after Stephen's martyrdom, which scatters the Jerusalem believers \"throughout the regions of Judea and Samaria,\" who then \"went about preaching the word\" (Acts 8:1-4). Acts 14:6 is a continuation of this Spirit-ordained pattern. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the Great Commission (Matt 28:19), which commands a deliberate \"going\" that this verse shows is sometimes accomplished through a \"fleeing.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): This passage informs missionary strategy, demonstrating that tactical withdrawal is a valid, Spirit-led option in the face of mortal danger.\n    *   ☐ Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"): Though not explicitly mentioned, the Holy Spirit is the unseen director of the mission (cf. Acts 13:2, 4; 16:6-7), guiding the apostles' steps through open and closed doors.\n    *   ☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The flight is not the point; it is the means to the end of proclaiming the gospel of salvation (Acts 14:7), which is the entire purpose of the journey.\n*   **Theological Tension / Paradox:** The passage holds in tension the virtues of boldness and prudence. In Iconium, the apostles \"spoke boldly for the Lord\" for a long time (14:3). Yet, faced with a credible murder plot, they fled. This resolves the false dichotomy between faith and common sense. True faith is not reckless; it is courageously obedient to God's leading, whether that means staying put or strategically relocating. This reflects Christ's own command to be \"wise as serpents and innocent as doves\" (Matt 10:16).\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ by demonstrating the outworking of His commission and commands. The apostles flee not to save their own lives for their own sake, but to preserve their lives for the sake of the gospel of Christ. Their actions are a testament to the supreme value they place on their message about Jesus, a message worth living—and relocating—to proclaim.\n",
