e could plant it down / The seed of His great grace\"\nA close-up, photorealistic shot of a hand letting a single, glowing seed fall from its palm onto dry, cracked earth. A single drop of water is about to land on the seed. The image is a tight macro, symbolizing the preciousness of the gospel being sown in new, hard ground. Warm amber light, shallow depth of field, shot on 35mm film.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: Outro lines 1-2 — \"To Lystra we will go / To Derbe we will run\"\nA cinematic still showing the two travelers arriving at the outskirts of a smaller, more rustic town (Lystra). They are looking toward it with determination, not fear. The landscape is rugged, the architecture simpler than the city they left. The mood is hopeful and resolute. Soft dawn gold palette, natural light.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-title\nAnchor: The Big Idea — \"Wise retreat is not cowardice but a divine strategy for redeploying gospel witnesses to new fields.\"\nA powerful cinematic image of two sets of footprints leading away from a pile of discarded stones on a dusty Roman road. The road stretches toward a distant, mountainous horizon under a vast, hopeful sky. The image captures the core theme: leaving danger behind to walk a new path of purpose. Sepia parchment and ochre palette, shot with an anamorphic lens for an epic feel.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-horizon\nAnchor: Christo-telic Horizon — The Great Commission enacted.\nA symbolic, abstract image. A map of the ancient Roman world is etched onto a stone tablet. From a single point labeled \"Jerusalem,\" glowing lines of light spread outwards, with one bright line tracing the path from Iconium to Lystra and Derbe, pushing into a previously dark region of the map. The image visualizes the unstoppable advance of the gospel. Deep indigo and gold palette.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n",
