      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-18 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\nεἶπεν μεγάλῃ τῇ φωνῇ· Ἀνάστηθι ἐπὶ τοὺς πόδας σου ὀρθός. καὶ ἥλατο καὶ περιεπάτει.\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | εἶπεν | eipen | G2036 | λέγω | V-AAI-3S | he said |\n| 2 | μεγάλῃ | megalē | G3173 | μέγας | A-DSF | with a great / loud |\n| 3 | τῇ | tē | G3588 | ὁ | T-DSF | the |\n| 4 | φωνῇ | phōnē | G5456 | φωνή | N-DSF | voice |\n| 5 | Ἀνάστηθι | Anasthēthi | G450 | ἀνίστημι | V-AAM-2S | Stand up! / Arise! |\n| 6 | ἐπὶ | epi | G1909 | ἐπί | Prep | upon |\n| 7 | τοὺς | tous | G3588 | ὁ | T-APM | the |\n| 8 | πόδας | podas | G4228 | πούς | N-APM | feet |\n| 9 | σου | sou | G4771 | σύ | P-2GS | of you / your |\n| 10 | ὀρθός | orthos | G3717 | ὀρθός | A-NSM | upright |\n| 11 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 12 | ἥλατο | hēlato | G242 | ἅλλομαι | V-AMI-3S | he leaped / sprang up |\n| 13 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 14 | περιεπάτει | periepatei | G4043 | περιπατέω | V-IAI-3S | he was walking / began to walk |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\nhe said with a great voice, \"Stand up upon your feet upright.\" And he leaped and was walking.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\nhe called out in a loud voice, \"Stand upright on your feet!\" And the man jumped up and began to walk.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\nhe said with a great [and authoritative] voice, \"Arise! Stand up on your feet, straight and upright!\" And in that instant, he sprang up [with a single powerful leap] and began to walk around [continuously and completely healed].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8-18 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<p>εἶπεν μεγάλῃ τῇ φωνῇ· Ἀνάστηθι ἐπὶ τοὺς πόδας σου ὀρθός. καὶ ἥλατο καὶ περιεπάτει.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>εἶπεν</td>\n<td>eipen</td>\n<td>G2036</td>\n<td>λέγω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3S</td>\n<td>he said</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>μεγάλῃ</td>\n<td>megalē</td>\n<td>G3173</td>\n<td>μέγας</td>\n<td>A-DSF</td>\n<td>with a great / loud</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>τῇ</td>\n<td>tē</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DSF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>φωνῇ</td>\n<td>phōnē</td>\n<td>G5456</td>\n<td>φωνή</td>\n<td>N-DSF</td>\n<td>voice</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Ἀνάστηθι</td>\n<td>Anasthēthi</td>\n<td>G450</td>\n<td>ἀνίστημι</td>\n<td>V-AAM-2S</td>\n<td>Stand up! / Arise!</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἐπὶ</td>\n<td>epi</td>\n<td>G1909</td>\n<td>ἐπί</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>upon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>τοὺς</td>\n<td>tous</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-APM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>πόδας</td>\n<td>podas</td>\n<td>G4228</td>\n<td>πούς</td>\n<td>N-APM</td>\n<td>feet</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>σου</td>\n<td>sou</td>\n<td>G4771</td>\n<td>σύ</td>\n<td>P-2GS</td>\n<td>of you / your</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>ὀρθός</td>\n<td>orthos</td>\n<td>G3717</td>\n<td>ὀρθός</td>\n<td>A-NSM</td>\n<td>upright</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>ἥλατο</td>\n<td>hēlato</td>\n<td>G242</td>\n<td>ἅλλομαι</td>\n<td>V-AMI-3S</td>\n<td>he leaped / sprang up</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>περιεπάτει</td>\n<td>periepatei</td>\n<td>G4043</td>\n<td>περιπατέω</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3S</td>\n<td>he was walking / began to walk</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>he said with a great voice, \"Stand up upon your feet upright.\" And he leaped and was walking.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>he called out in a loud voice, \"Stand upright on your feet!\" And the man jumped up and began to walk.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong></p>\n<p>he said with a great [and authoritative] voice, \"Arise! Stand up on your feet, straight and upright!\" And in that instant, he sprang up [with a single powerful leap] and began to walk around [continuously and completely healed].</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** The authoritative word of the gospel, when spoken in Spirit-given boldness and met with faith, has the power to command new life and bring immediate, radical transformation.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The passage addresses the condition of utter helplessness—physical and spiritual—that has existed from birth. It confronts our inability to stand on our own, to move, or to change our fundamental condition apart from a divine, external intervention.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Like the man at Lystra, we are often sitting passively in our brokenness. We hear the gospel proclaimed. We are confronted with the same need for a moment of faith—to believe that the command to \"arise\" is for us and that the power to obey is contained within the command itself.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before you were ever asked to walk, Christ died and rose again. The same power that raised Jesus from the dead (Eph 1:19-20) is the power at work in the gospel. You are not commanded to stand in your own strength. The command comes from the one who has already secured your new life. His word does not just invite; it creates.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When you hear a clear command from God's Word, act on it immediately. Do not analyze your ability; trust the ability of the One who commands.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a faith that expects God to act. Paul saw faith in the man *before* the miracle. Ask God to grow in you a faith that is ready to be made well.\n    *   *Relational:* Speak words of life and truth to those around you who are spiritually crippled by sin or despair. The gospel you carry has the same power to command them to \"arise.\"\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your sphere of influence, exercise the authority God has given you not for personal gain but to bring healing and restoration, always pointing away from yourself to Christ as the source of power.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals God's creative, restorative power. We worship the God whose word alone can make the lame leap and the dead arise. \"Lord Jesus, you are the Resurrection and the Life. At your command, what is broken is made whole and what is dead is brought to life. We praise you as the source of all power and healing.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> The authoritative word of the gospel, when spoken in Spirit-given boldness and met with faith, has the power to command new life and bring immediate, radical transformation.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The passage addresses the condition of utter helplessness—physical and spiritual—that has existed from birth. It confronts our inability to stand on our own, to move, or to change our fundamental condition apart from a divine, external intervention.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Like the man at Lystra, we are often sitting passively in our brokenness. We hear the gospel proclaimed. We are confronted with the same need for a moment of faith—to believe that the command to \"arise\" is for us and that the power to obey is contained within the command itself.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Before you were ever asked to walk, Christ died and rose again. The same power that raised Jesus from the dead (Eph 1:19-20) is the power at work in the gospel. You are not commanded to stand in your own strength. The command comes from the one who has already secured your new life. His word does not just invite; it creates.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> When you hear a clear command from God's Word, act on it immediately. Do not analyze your ability; trust the ability of the One who commands.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a faith that expects God to act. Paul saw faith in the man <em>before</em> the miracle. Ask God to grow in you a faith that is ready to be made well.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Speak words of life and truth to those around you who are spiritually crippled by sin or despair. The gospel you carry has the same power to command them to \"arise.\"</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your sphere of influence, exercise the authority God has given you not for personal gain but to bring healing and restoration, always pointing away from yourself to Christ as the source of power.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals God's creative, restorative power. We worship the God whose word alone can make the lame leap and the dead arise. \"Lord Jesus, you are the Resurrection and the Life. At your command, what is broken is made whole and what is dead is brought to life. We praise you as the source of all power and healing.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:10 — \"Stand upright on your feet.\"\nKEY TERM:     Ἀνάστηθι (Anasthēthi, \"Arise! / Stand up!\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: The gospel command has inherent power to create new life.\nIMAGE:        A man, lame from birth, leaping to his feet.\nAPPLICATION:  For myself: Act immediately on God's word, trusting His power.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to you, Lord, whose word brings the dead to life.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:10 — &quot;Stand upright on your feet.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>Ἀνάστηθι (Anasthēthi, &quot;Arise! / Stand up!&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>The gospel command has inherent power to create new life.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A man, lame from birth, leaping to his feet.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For myself: Act immediately on God&#x27;s word, trusting His power.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to you, Lord, whose word brings the dead to life.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever felt completely stuck, powerless to change a situation you've been in for as long as you can remember? In the ancient city of Lystra, a man lame from birth sat every day, just as he had the day before. But on this day, the Apostle Paul was preaching the gospel. Paul looked at him and saw something remarkable: \"faith to be made well\" (Acts 14:9).\n\nWhat happened next was electric. Paul didn't suggest physical therapy. He didn't offer a long-term recovery plan. He issued a command in the power of the risen Jesus, shouting, \"Stand upright on your feet!\" The Greek word for \"stand up\" is Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*), a word that echoes the power of resurrection. And in that instant, the man \"sprang up and began to walk.\" This wasn't just a healing; it was a creation. It was a picture of salvation itself. The word of the gospel doesn't just give advice; it imparts life. It commands us, spiritually lame from birth in our sin, to arise and walk in newness of life (Romans 6:4). The power to obey is found in the command itself, because the one who commands is the one who rose from the dead. This week, when you hear God's word, don't just listen to it. Leap.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt completely stuck, powerless to change a situation you've been in for as long as you can remember? In the ancient city of Lystra, a man lame from birth sat every day, just as he had the day before. But on this day, the Apostle Paul was preaching the gospel. Paul looked at him and saw something remarkable: \"faith to be made well\" (Acts 14:9).</p>\n<p>What happened next was electric. Paul didn't suggest physical therapy. He didn't offer a long-term recovery plan. He issued a command in the power of the risen Jesus, shouting, \"Stand upright on your feet!\" The Greek word for \"stand up\" is Ἀνάστηθι (<em>Anasthēthi</em>), a word that echoes the power of resurrection. And in that instant, the man \"sprang up and began to walk.\" This wasn't just a healing; it was a creation. It was a picture of salvation itself. The word of the gospel doesn't just give advice; it imparts life. It commands us, spiritually lame from birth in our sin, to arise and walk in newness of life (Romans 6:4). The power to obey is found in the command itself, because the one who commands is the one who rose from the dead. This week, when you hear God's word, don't just listen to it. Leap.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What specific phrase did Paul shout to the lame man?\n    A: \"Stand upright on your feet!\"\n2.  Why is the man's response of \"leaping\" and \"walking\" so significant?\n    A: It showed the healing was both instantaneous (the leap) and complete/continuous (the walking), not partial or temporary.\n3.  What does this miracle teach us about the power of the gospel message?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel is not just information but a divine, powerful word that can create new life and bring radical transformation where there was once helplessness. It is the power of the resurrected Christ at work.\n4.  Based on this story, how should I respond when I hear a clear command from God's Word?\n    A: I should act on it immediately, trusting in God's power to enable me to obey, rather than focusing on my own inability.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What specific phrase did Paul shout to the lame man?\n    A: \"Stand upright on your feet!\"</li>\n<li>Why is the man's response of \"leaping\" and \"walking\" so significant?\n    A: It showed the healing was both instantaneous (the leap) and complete/continuous (the walking), not partial or temporary.</li>\n<li>What does this miracle teach us about the power of the gospel message?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel is not just information but a divine, powerful word that can create new life and bring radical transformation where there was once helplessness. It is the power of the resurrected Christ at work.</li>\n<li>Based on this story, how should I respond when I hear a clear command from God's Word?\n    A: I should act on it immediately, trusting in God's power to enable me to obey, rather than focusing on my own inability.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered witness expands to the world.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: A key sign-miracle on the First Missionary Journey.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative miracle story, transformed into a declaration.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: Church Age, power of Christ demonstrated to pagans.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: Resurrection power bringing new life to the helpless.\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\n\nGate 1: PASS — Every line is justified by the exegesis of the command and response.\nGate 2: PASS — The verses map the context (v.9) and result (v.10b) around the Chorus's command (v.10a).\nGate 3: PASS — Elpis tone is strong; readiness for God's command is the theme.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of feet, dust, stone, and leaping is from the text.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian exegesis is primary; Jewish Midrash on Ps 146 informs the \"divine prerogative\" feel.\nGate 6: PASS — The entire pericope (vv. 8-10) is covered.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 is past tense (\"sat\"), Chorus is imperative (\"stand\"), Bridge pivots to \"I hear.\"\nGate 8: PASS — The Phi reveal is the Bridge's turn to personal faith.\nGate 9: PASS — \"Stand Up\" and \"Leap Now\" fall on strong downbeats.\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives and hard consonants in the command; liquids in the result.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up from the constricted state in V1 to the command in the Chorus.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables, well within Miller's Law.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between blocks.\nGate 14: PASS — The song ends with the finality of \"walk.\"\nGate 15: PASS — \"Upright On Your Feet\" is a clear, memorable headline.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent trochaic/dactylic feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep theology (resurrection power in the command) is compressed into simple lyrics.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are bait (the story), Chorus is the barb (the command).\nGate 19: PASS — The Bridge contains the vocative \"O Lord\" and the first-person \"I hear.\"\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge: \"I stand because You spoke the word\" is a clear gospel hinge.\nGate 21: PASS — Strict AABB rhyme scheme declared and executed with exact rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single ` ```text ` fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts are verified per line (6-8 syllables).\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Upright\" is short, concrete, from the hook, and memorable.\n\n```text\nTitle: Upright\nStyle: Raw Americana, gospel blues, foot-stomping rhythm, single acoustic guitar, gravelly male vocal, upright bass, kick drum on all four beats, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nLame feet knew the dust (A)\nYears of settled rust (A)\nNever stood up tall (B)\nWaiting for the call (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nUpright on your feet (A)\nTaste a mercy sweet (A)\nHear the voice command (B)\nRise up in this land (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nFaith seen in the eyes (A)\nHope begins to rise (A)\nPower in the sound (B)\nShakes the solid ground (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nUpright on your feet (A)\nTaste a mercy sweet (A)\nHear the voice command (B)\nRise up in this land (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nThe word that raised the dead (A)\nIs the word that now is said (A)\nO Lord, I hear Your call (B)\nBefore Your voice I fall (B)\n\n[Outro]\nLeap up from the stone (A)\nPower not my own (A)\nNow I walk in light (B)\nBy Your word of might (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n",
