      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The apostolic command given to the lame man at Lystra and the man's immediate response.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** The authoritative word of God's messenger, empowered by the Holy Spirit, has the creative power to bring instantaneous, complete physical restoration to those who receive it in faith.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** The proclaimed word of Christ has inherent power to command new life into being, resulting in immediate and visible transformation.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The apostolic command given to the lame man at Lystra and the man's immediate response.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> The authoritative word of God's messenger, empowered by the Holy Spirit, has the creative power to bring instantaneous, complete physical restoration to those who receive it in faith.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> The proclaimed word of Christ has inherent power to command new life into being, resulting in immediate and visible transformation.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This miracle at Lystra serves as a powerful sign authenticating Paul's apostleship and the truth of his message to a purely pagan Gentile audience, demonstrating that the power of the risen Christ is not confined to Jerusalem or the Jewish people.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This event occurs during Paul and Barnabas's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13-14). It follows their persecution in Iconium (14:1-7) and precedes the Lystrans' attempt to worship them as gods (14:11-18). The healing is the catalyst for the subsequent conflict over true versus false worship.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):** The genre is Historical Narrative, specifically a miracle story. The hermeneutic requires us to read this as a factual historical event, not an allegory. We must distinguish description (what happened) from prescription (what is always commanded). The narrative highlights the source of the power (Christ), the means (apostolic proclamation), and the validation it provides for the gospel message.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event is firmly in the Church Age, under the Dispensation of Grace. It marks a key moment in the fulfillment of the Great Commission, as the gospel's power is demonstrated far from the geographic and ethnic center of Israel, fulfilling the promise that the Abrahamic blessing would reach all nations (Gen 12:3).\n*   **Author & Attribution:** Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing around AD 60-62. His medical background may inform the precise description of the man's condition (\"lame from birth,\" v. 8) and the totality of his healing.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The preceding verse (14:9) is crucial: Paul, \"fixing his gaze on him and seeing that he had faith to be made well,\" provides the basis for the command. The healing is not random; it is a response to perceived faith. The subsequent verses (14:11-13) show the pagan misunderstanding of this power, as they deify Paul and Barnabas, creating the crisis that Paul's next sermon must address.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This healing is a deliberate and striking parallel to Peter's healing of the lame man at the Temple gate in Acts 3:1-10 [Pericope: Acts 3:1-12 · source: NA28]. Luke pairs these stories to establish Paul's authority as an apostle on par with Peter. Both men were crippled from birth, both healings were public, both involved a direct command, and both resulted in the man leaping and walking. The key difference is the audience: Peter's miracle was to Jews in Jerusalem; Paul's is to Gentiles in pagan Anatolia. This miracle also fulfills the messianic promise of Isaiah 35:6, \"then shall the lame man leap like a deer.\"\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This miracle at Lystra serves as a powerful sign authenticating Paul's apostleship and the truth of his message to a purely pagan Gentile audience, demonstrating that the power of the risen Christ is not confined to Jerusalem or the Jewish people.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This event occurs during Paul and Barnabas's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13-14). It follows their persecution in Iconium (14:1-7) and precedes the Lystrans' attempt to worship them as gods (14:11-18). The healing is the catalyst for the subsequent conflict over true versus false worship.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):</strong> The genre is Historical Narrative, specifically a miracle story. The hermeneutic requires us to read this as a factual historical event, not an allegory. We must distinguish description (what happened) from prescription (what is always commanded). The narrative highlights the source of the power (Christ), the means (apostolic proclamation), and the validation it provides for the gospel message.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> This event is firmly in the Church Age, under the Dispensation of Grace. It marks a key moment in the fulfillment of the Great Commission, as the gospel's power is demonstrated far from the geographic and ethnic center of Israel, fulfilling the promise that the Abrahamic blessing would reach all nations (Gen 12:3).</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing around AD 60-62. His medical background may inform the precise description of the man's condition (\"lame from birth,\" v. 8) and the totality of his healing.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The preceding verse (14:9) is crucial: Paul, \"fixing his gaze on him and seeing that he had faith to be made well,\" provides the basis for the command. The healing is not random; it is a response to perceived faith. The subsequent verses (14:11-13) show the pagan misunderstanding of this power, as they deify Paul and Barnabas, creating the crisis that Paul's next sermon must address.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This healing is a deliberate and striking parallel to Peter's healing of the lame man at the Temple gate in Acts 3:1-10 [Pericope: Acts 3:1-12 · source: NA28]. Luke pairs these stories to establish Paul's authority as an apostle on par with Peter. Both men were crippled from birth, both healings were public, both involved a direct command, and both resulted in the man leaping and walking. The key difference is the audience: Peter's miracle was to Jews in Jerusalem; Paul's is to Gentiles in pagan Anatolia. This miracle also fulfills the messianic promise of Isaiah 35:6, \"then shall the lame man leap like a deer.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately AD 46-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Lystra was a Roman colony in the region of Lycaonia, in modern-day south-central Turkey. It was a relatively small, non-Hellenized town on a minor trade route, unlike the major centers of Antioch or Ephesus. Its isolation meant its paganism was more local and rustic, which helps explain the specific reaction of identifying Paul and Barnabas with Zeus and Hermes (v. 12).\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The immediate audience was the crowd at Lystra, composed of local Lycaonians who spoke their own dialect (v. 11) and likely some Latin-speaking Roman officials. There was likely no synagogue, as none is mentioned, making this a direct-to-pagan ministry. Luke's wider audience for the book of Acts is Theophilus and the early church, for whom this story would serve as a powerful validation of the Gentile mission.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is carefully constructing his narrative to demonstrate the continuity and expansion of the gospel. By mirroring Peter's miracle, he pastorally affirms to his readers that the power and authority resident in the Jerusalem apostles is the very same power and authority at work in Paul's Gentile ministry. It is a defense of both Paul and his gospel.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately AD 46-48.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Lystra was a Roman colony in the region of Lycaonia, in modern-day south-central Turkey. It was a relatively small, non-Hellenized town on a minor trade route, unlike the major centers of Antioch or Ephesus. Its isolation meant its paganism was more local and rustic, which helps explain the specific reaction of identifying Paul and Barnabas with Zeus and Hermes (v. 12).</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> The immediate audience was the crowd at Lystra, composed of local Lycaonians who spoke their own dialect (v. 11) and likely some Latin-speaking Roman officials. There was likely no synagogue, as none is mentioned, making this a direct-to-pagan ministry. Luke's wider audience for the book of Acts is Theophilus and the early church, for whom this story would serve as a powerful validation of the Gentile mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke is carefully constructing his narrative to demonstrate the continuity and expansion of the gospel. By mirroring Peter's miracle, he pastorally affirms to his readers that the power and authority resident in the Jerusalem apostles is the very same power and authority at work in Paul's Gentile ministry. It is a defense of both Paul and his gospel.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** A man, crippled from birth, is commanded to stand. He does so, leaping up and walking perfectly. This is a supernatural, instantaneous healing.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:**\n    *   The command Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*, \"Stand up! / Arise!\") is a potent aorist active imperative. It's a sharp, decisive command demanding immediate action. The root word, ἀνίστημι (*anistēmi*), is the same root used for resurrection (e.g., Acts 17:31), subtly linking this act of healing to the ultimate life-giving power of Christ's own rising from the dead.\n    *   The result is described with two verbs. First, ἥλατο (*hēlato*, \"he leaped\"), an aorist middle indicative, indicating a sudden, reflexive action performed by the man himself. Second, περιεπάτει (*periepatei*, \"he was walking\"), an imperfect active indicative. The imperfect tense here denotes continuous, ongoing action. He didn't just stumble a few steps; he began walking around confidently and without cessation, a visible proof of his complete cure.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The central image is of a man moving from powerlessness to power, from being grounded to leaping. This is a physical picture of salvation itself: a person spiritually \"lame from birth\" in sin (cf. Eph 2:1) is commanded by the gospel to \"arise,\" and through the power of Christ, is enabled to stand and \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4).\n    *   **Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"):** A person lame from birth suffers from severe muscle atrophy and undeveloped neuromuscular pathways. An instantaneous leap would require not just the healing of the original defect but the supernatural creation of muscle mass and the instant writing of motor control programs to the brain. The physics of the \"leap\" confirms the miraculous nature of the event, far beyond simple healing.\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment (per-Unit):** This act is a direct fulfillment of messianic prophecy. Isaiah 35:6 promised that in the age of salvation, \"the lame man [shall] leap like a deer.\" Paul's action, in the power of Jesus the Messiah, brings this prophetic promise to life in a pagan city, showing the scope of Messiah's kingdom. [PROPHECY]\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter:</strong> A man, crippled from birth, is commanded to stand. He does so, leaping up and walking perfectly. This is a supernatural, instantaneous healing.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong><ul>\n<li>The command Ἀνάστηθι (<em>Anasthēthi</em>, \"Stand up! / Arise!\") is a potent aorist active imperative. It's a sharp, decisive command demanding immediate action. The root word, ἀνίστημι (<em>anistēmi</em>), is the same root used for resurrection (e.g., Acts 17:31), subtly linking this act of healing to the ultimate life-giving power of Christ's own rising from the dead.</li>\n<li>The result is described with two verbs. First, ἥλατο (<em>hēlato</em>, \"he leaped\"), an aorist middle indicative, indicating a sudden, reflexive action performed by the man himself. Second, περιεπάτει (<em>periepatei</em>, \"he was walking\"), an imperfect active indicative. The imperfect tense here denotes continuous, ongoing action. He didn't just stumble a few steps; he began walking around confidently and without cessation, a visible proof of his complete cure.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):</strong> The central image is of a man moving from powerlessness to power, from being grounded to leaping. This is a physical picture of salvation itself: a person spiritually \"lame from birth\" in sin (cf. Eph 2:1) is commanded by the gospel to \"arise,\" and through the power of Christ, is enabled to stand and \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4).<ul>\n<li><strong>Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"):</strong> A person lame from birth suffers from severe muscle atrophy and undeveloped neuromuscular pathways. An instantaneous leap would require not just the healing of the original defect but the supernatural creation of muscle mass and the instant writing of motor control programs to the brain. The physics of the \"leap\" confirms the miraculous nature of the event, far beyond simple healing.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment (per-Unit):</strong> This act is a direct fulfillment of messianic prophecy. Isaiah 35:6 promised that in the age of salvation, \"the lame man [shall] leap like a deer.\" Paul's action, in the power of Jesus the Messiah, brings this prophetic promise to life in a pagan city, showing the scope of Messiah's kingdom. [PROPHECY]</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment (Whole-Passage):** This event is part of a larger pattern of \"signs and wonders\" that authenticate God's messengers (Acts 2:43; 5:12; 2 Cor 12:12). It fulfills the promise of Jesus that his followers would do \"greater works\" (John 14:12) because He went to the Father, extending His healing ministry through them by the Spirit. [PROPHECY] The healing of the lame specifically was a sign of Jesus' own messianic ministry (Matt 11:5), and its continuation through the apostles confirms they operate in His authority. [TYPE]\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif is God's power to restore what is broken from birth. It begins with the curse of the Fall (Gen 3), is promised to be reversed in the Messianic age (Isa 35:6), is demonstrated in the ministry of Jesus (John 5:1-9; John 9:1-7), is delegated to His apostles for both Jews (Acts 3:1-10) and Gentiles (Acts 14:10), and will find its ultimate fulfillment in the resurrection body and the New Creation, where there will be no more pain or crying (Rev 21:4). The Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the Resurrection, the source of all restorative power. The hinge-of-hinges is Christ's own victory over death, which unleashes this creative power into the world. The terminus verse for this motif is Philippians 3:21, which speaks of the transformation of our \"lowly body to be like his glorious body, by the power that enables him even to subject all things to himself.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ **Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\"):** Demonstrates the present power and authority of the ascended Christ, working through His apostle.\n    *   ☐ **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):** This is a work of the Holy Spirit, who empowers the apostolic witness with \"signs and wonders\" (cf. Rom 15:19; Heb 2:4).\n    *   ☐ **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** The physical healing is a visible sign of the spiritual salvation offered in the gospel—instantaneous, complete, and received by faith.\n    *   ☐ **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** Validates the legitimacy of the Gentile mission and the apostolic authority upon which the church is built (Eph 2:20).\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis:** Conservative Christian commentators universally see this as a key parallel to Acts 3, validating Paul's ministry. Jewish tradition has stories of healing by righteous men (e.g., Honi the Circle-Drawer), but the instantaneous nature and the explicit link to the authority of a specific person (Jesus) is distinct. The Midrash on Psalm 146:8 (\"The LORD opens the eyes of the blind; The LORD raises up those who are bowed down\") sees this as a divine prerogative, which heightens the shock of the Lystrans, who immediately attribute this divine power to the men standing before them.\n",
