octrine of the Holy Spirit\"):</strong> This is a work of the Holy Spirit, who empowers the apostolic witness with \"signs and wonders\" (cf. Rom 15:19; Heb 2:4).</li>\n<li>☐ <strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):</strong> The physical healing is a visible sign of the spiritual salvation offered in the gospel—instantaneous, complete, and received by faith.</li>\n<li>☐ <strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):</strong> Validates the legitimacy of the Gentile mission and the apostolic authority upon which the church is built (Eph 2:20).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Tripartite Synthesis:</strong> Conservative Christian commentators universally see this as a key parallel to Acts 3, validating Paul's ministry. Jewish tradition has stories of healing by righteous men (e.g., Honi the Circle-Drawer), but the instantaneous nature and the explicit link to the authority of a specific person (Jesus) is distinct. The Midrash on Psalm 146:8 (\"The LORD opens the eyes of the blind; The LORD raises up those who are bowed down\") sees this as a divine prerogative, which heightens the shock of the Lystrans, who immediately attribute this divine power to the men standing before them.</li>\n</ul>",
