"cold call\" to a purely pagan audience, testing the gospel's power to penetrate a worldview utterly alien to its biblical presuppositions.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Author &amp; Attribution</strong>: The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing a historical account to Theophilus (Luke 1:1-4; Acts 1:1). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Gravitational Neighbors</strong>: The verse is triggered by the preceding miracle: Paul, seeing the faith of a man \"lame from his mother's womb,\" commands him to stand, and he is healed instantly (Acts 14:8-10). It immediately causes the subsequent action: the priest of Zeus brings oxen and garlands to offer sacrifice to Barnabas (identified as Zeus) and Paul (identified as Hermes) (Acts 14:12-13).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Apostolic Deflection of Worship</strong>: In Acts 3:12, after healing another lame man, Peter immediately corrects the crowd: \"Men of Israel, why do you wonder at this, or why do you stare at us, as though by our own power or piety we have made him walk?\" [Pericope: Acts 3:11-26 · source: NA28].</li>\n<li><strong>Confronting Pagan Idolatry</strong>: Paul's sermon at the Areopagus in Athens directly confronts their worship of \"an unknown god\" (Acts 17:22-31) [Pericope: Acts 17:16-34 · source: NA28].</li>\n<li><strong>Creature Worship Condemned</strong>: The theological root of the Lystrans' error is diagnosed in Romans 1:25, where fallen humanity \"exchanged the truth about God for a lie and worshiped and served the creature rather than the Creator\" [Pericope: Rom 1:18-32 · source: NA28].</li>\n<li><strong>The True Incarnation (Contrast)</strong>: The crowd's cry is a pagan parody of the central truth of the gospel: God truly did come down in the likeness of men in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1: