e act. PASS — All four point to the same action: deflecting glory from the human instrument to God.\n</code></pre>",
        "slide_deck_sidecar": "## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"11\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:11 — Pagan Misinterpretation of a Divine Miracle\nWhen the crowd at Lystra witnessed Paul heal a lame man, they did not turn to the one true God. Instead, they defaulted to their pagan worldview, shouting in their native tongue that their own gods, Zeus and Hermes, had visited them in human form.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 9 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n",
        "slide_deck_sidecar_html": "<h2>Slide Deck Sidecar</h2>\n<h2>```markdown</h2>\n<p>book: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"11\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre</p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Acts 14:11 — Pagan Misinterpretation of a Divine Miracle</h1>\n<p>When the crowd at Lystra witnessed Paul heal a lame man, they did not turn to the one true God. Instead, they defaulted to their pagan worldview, shouting in their native tongue that their own gods, Zeus and Hermes, had visited them in human form.</p>\n<p><em>Slide deck: 7 sections, 9 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.</em></p>",
        "cover_art_prompts": "## Cover Art Prompts\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 3-4 — \"The dusty market square / A charge is in the air\"\nA cinematic still from a low angle in a dusty, sun-drenched Anatolian town square. A recently healed man is on his feet, looking astonished, while a crowd begins to surge forward, their faces a mixture of awe and manic excitement. Paul and Barnabas are small, unassuming figures in the center. Sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. Shot on 35mm film, anamorphic lens, shallow depth of field, photorealistic.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 1-2 — \"You shout the wrong gods' names / You feed the pagan flames\"\nA dramatic, high-contrast chiaroscuro shot focusing on the open mouths of the shouting Lystran crowd. In the background, out of focus, a pagan altar with small flames beginning to flicker. The emotion is fervent, ecstatic, but misguided. Ember-and-shadow palette. Volumetric light cutting through the dust.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V2 lines 3-4 — \"You bring the priest and bull / Your mind is dark and full\"\nA cinematic shot of a priest of Zeus, adorned in rustic pagan vestments, leading a large ox with garlands around its horns through the frenzied crowd toward the apostles. The focus is on the sacrificial animal, a symbol of the profound theological error. Sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. Natural light, photorealistic.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-4\nAnchor: Bridge lines 3-4 — \"But O Lord, You are real / Your truth is what can heal\"\nA symbolic image. An ancient, leather-bound scroll representing the Word of God is open. A single, pure beam of golden-hour light illuminates the text, cutting through a dark, dusty room. The focus is on the light hitting the words, representing truth dispelling the darkness of myth and idolatry. Warm amber, low-key key-light, gold-hour tones.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: Outro lines 1-2 — \"Not gods who came in myth / But Word that drew a breath\"\nA highly symbolic and reverent image focusing on a simple wooden manger. The scene is quiet and still, bathed in a soft, divine light from an unseen source. This image of the Nativity serves as the ultimate answer to the Lystran's cry, representing the true Incarnation. Deep indigo, starfield, volumetric blues.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no depiction of the Christ child, only the empty manger and the light.\n```\n```nano-banana-title\nAnchor: The central image of the passage — a divine miracle misinterpreted.\nAn ultra-high-resolution cinematic still. Two simple, travel-worn missionaries stand back-to-back, their hands raised in a gesture of protest. They are encircled by a frenzied pagan crowd, some of whom are trying to lay sacrificial garlands at their feet. The lighting is dramatic, like a Caravaggio painting, with shafts of light breaking through a dusty haze. The core tension between the true miracle and the false worship is palpable. Sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-horizon\nAnchor: The Christo-telic Horizon — the true Incarnation that answers the pagan myth.\nA symbolic and majestic image of the Word becoming flesh. A beam of pure, heavenly light descends into a humble, first-century stable, illuminating the very dust particles in the air. The light falls upon an empty wooden manger, implying a sacred presence without depicting it. This is the true \"coming down,\" full of grace and truth, not myth. Deep indigo and warm gold palette.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no depiction of any person or infant.\n```\n",
